<DOCNO> XIE19970718.0002 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup:Kenya's Opposition Bids up for Talks with </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 18 (Xinhua) -- The stage is set for further
confrontation in Kenya over constitutional reforms as the
opposition are demanding more when the government softens its
originally very hard tune on the issue.
</P>
<P>
Opposition leaders said today that they are not sure that the
government is really moving to meet their demands and thus will
stick to their crusade for change in the eastern African country.
</P>
<P>
The opposition National Convention Executive Council (NCEC)
vowed Thursday to push ahead with mass actions in July and August#,
including a nationwide strike on August 8 to paralyze business
and several rallies in major cities around the country.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, opposition members of parliament gave Moi nine
pre-conditions for expected talks between Moi and the opposition
next week, urging Moi to publicly pledge to undertake the reforms
before the forthcoming general elections.
</P>
<P>
They also demanded all unviersities closed during the
campaign for constitutional reforms be re-opened, all people
arrested during the broken-up rallies be released and all rallies
on constitutional reforms be held with no need to seek permits.
</P>
<P>
The opposition parties said now they want the government to
immediately start "legislative mechanics" for undertaking
comprehensive constitutional reforms, instead of minimum reforms
they had advocated before.
</P>
<P>
They have dismissed President Daniel arap Moi's announcement
issued Wednesday that licences for rallies will be granted
automatically on application.
</P>
<P>
Although Moi's announcement is widely regarded as a
remarkable concession to the reform demands, the opposition said
it was just a "favor," arguing the issue "now is not about favors
but serious constitutional reforms."
</P>
<P>
In another key step towards reforms, Kenya's ruling party
Kenyan African National Union (KANU) Thursday recommended that
the government put forward a bill in parliament for enactment of
a commission to review the constitution and make proposals.
</P>
<P>
Kenyan Vice-President George Saitoti, holding the same post
in KANU, said KANU further suggested the government issue a
Statute Law bill in the current session of the parliament to
allow the repeal or amendment of laws charged as oppressive.
</P>
<P>
These laws include the Public Order Act on public rallies,
the Preservation of Public Security Act which allows detention
without trial, as well as other nine laws.
</P>
<P>
However, the opposition parties responded the KANU's shift
with deep scepticism, saying they should wait to see if the KANU,
which has a majority in the parliament, can take actions
"genuinely".
</P>
<P>
From May to July, violence has been escalating when the
opposition repeatedly tried to hold rallies without government
permit in a bid to press for constitutional reforms before the
general elections. All the rallies were broken up by the police.
</P>
<P>
Under the current constitution, any candidate, if he wins no
less than 25 percent of votes respectively in five of the eight
provinces of Kenya, he can be qualified as a legal president.
</P>
<P>
The opposition urges to change the clause, demanding that the
future president should get more than 50 percent of the total
votes nationwide otherwise form a coalition government with other
parties.
</P>
<P>
The demand was turned down by the 73-year-old Moi, who has
ruled the country for 19 years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
