<HEADLINE> Xinhua International News Summary at 1600 GMT, July 18 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW -- The latest crisis on the Mir space station will be
over soon as Earth and the Russian-U.S. crew restored a computer
link on Thursday to allow experts to help the cosmonauts repair
the craft, the Interfax news agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
Interfax quoted mission control chief Vladimir Solovyov as
saying that the station's batteries have been charged to a
sufficient extent to allow the station to rotate.
</P>
<P>
Solovyov told reporters on Thursday evening that Mir's
orientation towards the sun would be restored on Friday morning
and that the temperature and humidity inside the station are
normal.
</P>
<P>
BRUSSELS -- NATO and Russia held the first meeting of their
Permanent Joint Council at ambassadorial level on at NATO
headquarters in Brussels today.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was attended by NATO Secretary General Javier
Solana, Russian special envoy Vitaly Churkin and the 16
ambassadors of NATO member countries.
</P>
<P>
In a joint statement issued after the meeting, the two sides
said that they had formally adopted the organizational
arrangements and rules of procedures for the Permanent Joint
Council. 
</P>
</TEXT>
