<DOCNO> XIE19970718.0005 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yeltsin's Military Reform Plan Unveiled </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 18 (Xinhua) -- Sweeping changes to reorganize
Russia's armed forces and slash troop numbers by nearly a third
were unveiled by the Kremlin today, two days after Russian
President Boris Yeltsin signed decrees about the reforms.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin's decrees, issued on Wednesday, have not been published
in full but the Kremlin released some details on Friday, the
Interfax news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Troops will be cut by 500,000 to 1.2 million by the end of next
year in a series of measures designed to turn the conscript-based
forces into a leaner professional fighting machine.
</P>
<P>
Strategic missile troops, military space forces and military
space air defense troops are to be regrouped into one force called
the strategic missile force. Air defense troops will merge with
the air force.
</P>
<P>
The first 200,000 personnel will be discharged by the end of
this year.
</P>
<P>
Funds raised from privatizing some military organizations, and
the sale of property and equipment to be taken out of service, are
to be set aside to help discharged servicemen, reports said.
</P>
<P>
Defense spending for 1997 was set at 88.3 trillion roubles
(15.3 billion U.S. dollars) but was later reduced as part of
budget cuts. Officials say the military have so far got only 22
trillion roubles (3.82 billion U.S dollars).
</P>
<P>
Criticism of Yeltsin's reforms was prompt. Igor Rodionov, whom
Yeltsin sacked as defense minister in May for failing to carry out
reforms, today accused the president and the government of
destabilizing the army by launching "irresponsible" reforms.
</P>
<P>
Ousted security aide Alexander Lebed, a former army general,
said he was not optimistic about the reforms. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
