<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NATO, Russia Hold First Joint Council Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, July 18 (Xinhua) -- NATO and Russia held the first
meeting of their Permanent Joint Council at ambassadorial level on
at NATO headquarters in Brussels today.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was attended by NATO Secretary General Javier
Solana, Russian special envoy Vitaly Churkin and the 16
ambassadors of NATO member countries.
</P>
<P>
In a joint statement issued after the meeting, the two sides
said that they had formally adopted the organizational
arrangements and rules of procedures for the Permanent Joint
Council.
</P>
<P>
The meeting also agreed on the work schedule leading up to the
first Ministerial meeting of the Council planned in the week of
September 22, on the fringe of the United Nations General Assembly.
</P>
<P>
"All participants welcomed the holding of the first meeting of
the NATO-Russia Permanent Joint Council and expressed their
determination to continue the work in a positive spirit," the
statement said.
</P>
<P>
The Joint Council was created by the NATO-Russia Founding Act,
signed on May 27 in Paris, providing the two sides a new forum for
consultation, cooperation and possible joint decision-making.
</P>
<P>
The Council, which has a secretariat at NATO headquarters, is
chaired by NATO Secretary General, Russian ambassador to NATO and
one rotating representative of the 16 NATO members. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970718.0010 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Wants to Join EU: Chernomyrdin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, July 18 (Xinhua) -- Russia wants to join the European
Union (EU), but it has to sort things out at home first, visiting
Russian Prime Minister Victor Chernomyrdin said here today.
</P>
<P>
Chernomyrdin made the remark at a press conference in Brussels
after lengthy talks with Jacques Santer, president of the European
Commission, the EU's executive body.
</P>
<P>
He told reporters that what they were doing at the EU
headquarters was "directed at one point" -- making preparations to
join the EU, just as Russian President Boris Yeltsin once said.
</P>
<P>
However, Chernonmyrdin said that the deep restructuring process
underway in Russia's economy limited the immediate scope for the
Russian authorities to meet requests for commitments, either from
the EU or the World Trade Organization (WTO).
</P>
<P>
He held out hope that negotiations on Russia's accession to the
WTO could be completed by the end of 1998, thus underlining the
importance for Russia of early accession to the WTO.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that both Russia and the Commission had
expressed satisfaction at the prospect of beginning substantive
talks soon in Geneva in regard to WTO accession.
</P>
<P>
When asked about the prospects of Russia becoming an EU member,
Santer said that economic reforms which had been undertaken by the
Russian authorities in a determined manner had given him
confidence in that regard.
</P>
<P>
He said that the EU would see greater interlinks established
with Russia in the near future, adding that the same would happen
to their bilateral political talks as their economic cooperation
went to an "even deeper level."
</P>
<P>
On the issue of the EU's anti-dumping policy, Chernomyrdin said
they discussed the matter in great details and reached a better
mutual understanding though there still existed points of
disagreement.
</P>
<P>
In regard to bilateral trade in textiles and clothing, both
sides noted that negotiations on a new agreement had been going on
for some time and that a certain progress had been made. They
agreed to aim at obtaining a mutually balanced agreement within
the shortest possible time. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
