<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Crisis on Mir Over Soon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 18 (Xinhua) -- The latest crisis on the Mir space
station will be over soon as Earth and the Russian-U.S. crew
restored a computer link on Thursday to allow experts to help the
cosmonauts repair the craft, the Interfax news agency reported
today.
</P>
<P>
Interfax quoted mission control chief Vladimir Solovyov as
saying that the station's batteries have been charged to a
sufficient extent to allow the station to rotate.
</P>
<P>
Solovyov told reporters on Thursday evening that Mir's
orientation towards the sun would be restored on Friday morning
and that the temperature and humidity inside the station are
normal.
</P>
<P>
Mission control has told the crew to sleep and then rest for
two days in a bid to recover their strength. Further repairs of
the Mir energy system, involving a space walk, have been postponed
while the crew rest.
</P>
<P>
The Mir lost all power on Thursday when the crew accidentally
disconnected a vital cable. But the three-man team remained safe
and quickly began repairing the damage.
</P>
<P>
With the orientation system down, Mir twisted chaotically for
several hours before it could be stabilized by firing thrusters on
the Soyuz capsule which is docked at the station.
</P>
<P>
The three-man crew had been forced to spend time in the Soyuz,
which would have brought them back to Earth in an emergency.
</P>
<P>
Mir has been in trouble since June 25, when a cargo craft
slammed into the station during a manual docking, piercing the
Spektr module and depriving Mir of up to half of its energy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
