<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada's Wholesale Trade Up Slightly in May </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, July 18 (Xinhua) -- Canada's wholesale trade increased
one percent in May to reach a total of 17.1 billion U.S. dollars,
Statistics Canada reported today.
</P>
<P>
Canada's wholesale trade have increased in all but four months
since the beginning of 1996, the federal statistics agency said.
</P>
<P>
In May, the largest monthly increases in percentage terms were
recorded by wholesalers of farm machinery, farm-related products
and paper products.
</P>
<P>
Canadian wholesalers of farm machinery reported sales increases
of more than 10 percent in April and May. Sales of farm machinery
have been generally rising since mid-1995.
</P>
<P>
"Some of that strength can be attributed to low interest rates
which make the purchase of new equipment more attractive," the
agency said.
</P>
<P>
In Canada, computer sales have slowed in the last few months
after a period of general increases that started around mid-1995.
</P>
<P>
"This may reflect some supply problems of key computer
components and a weaker demand," the agency noted.
</P>
<P>
After two months of strong declines, computer sales were up 0.5
percent in May from the previous month. However, sales were down
3.8 percent compared to May 1996.
</P>
<P>
The inventories of wholesalers remained unchanged in May at 24
billion dollars, following a period of general increases beginning
around mid-1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
