<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Bans Illegal Publications </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, July 18 (Xinhua) -- Some 3,400 different illegally
published books with about 1.16 million copies in circulation have
been seized this year in China, the Press and Publications
Administration announced here today.
</P>
<P>
At a national meeting on stricter book market controls, Yang
Muzhi, the administration's deputy director, said that one
publishing house has been closed down, four have been temporarily
closed, and six have been given a warning for selling publishing
licenses or publishing bad books. And 956 books with problems were
discovered before they were printed.
</P>
<P>
Yang said the fight against illegal publishing must continue
and publishing houses must produce better books that respond to
the Party's and the people's demands.
</P>
<P>
China has 564 publishing houses nationwide, that turned out 7.1
billion books last year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
