<HEADLINE> Indian Ministers Decide to Stay </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, July 18 (Xinhua)-- Three Indian ministers loyal to
Laloo Prasad Yadav, president of the newly floated Rashtriya
Janata Dal, today announced their decision to continue as
ministers as long as their party is part of the ruling United
Front (UF) and pledged support to Prime Minister Inder Kumar
Gujral and UF's common minimum program.
</P>
<P>
"We have revised our decision to resign in view of statements
issued by the Front convener, N. Chandrababu Naidu, and President
of Dravida Mummetra Kazhagam (DMK) M. Karunanidhi, that the core
group of the Front had not taken any decision to keep our party
out of the UF," Food Minister Raghuvansh Prasad Singh said here.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the reported decision of the UF's core group last
night that the Rashtriya Janata Dal should be kept away, Singh
said to reporters at his residence that it was part of a
deep-rooted conspiracy to break the UF. He, however, refused to
divulge who all were behind the conspiracy.
</P>
<P>
He asked the Front leadership to immediately convene a meeting
of the full Steering Committee to decide whether his party should
remain in the Front. The core group of the UF decided to have such
meeting on July 25.
</P>
<P>
The Janata Dal, the major constituent of the UF, was split into
two factions early this month. While Sharad Yadav is heading the
Janata Dal, his arch rival Laloo Prasad Yadav is leading newly
floated Rashriya Janata Dal. Sharad Yadav, supported by some UF
constituents, is strongly against the entry of Laloo's party into
the UF. Laloo Prasad has time and again said that his party would
continue to support the UF government.  
</P>
</TEXT>
