<HEADLINE> Advanced Maritime Position System to Be Operational </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, July 18 (Xinhua) -- China will put a state-of-the-art
satellite guidance system for ocean-going ships into operation on
July 21.
</P>
<P>
The global positioning system will go into operation first in
the cities of Shanghai, Tianjin, Qinhuangdao, Dalian and Qingdao,
providing round-the-clock service with the help of 21 satellites.
</P>
<P>
The system will bring the mean error down from the 100
meters set by the conventional GPS system to about five meters,
said Wang Zhiyi, director of the Shanghai Maritime Safety
Administration.
</P>
<P>
The global positioning system can be used for both civilian
and military purposes.
</P>
<P>
China will build 20 ground stations by the year 2000 to allow
the system to cover all its coastal waters.  
</P>
</TEXT>
