<DOCNO> XIE19970718.0035 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-18 14:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russian Envoy Calls for Compromise on Cyprus Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, July 18 (Xinhua) -- A top Russian envoy called here
today for compromise between Greek and Turkish Cypriot sides in a
bid to find solutions to the Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters after an hour-long meeting with Cypriot
President Glafcos Clerides, Vladimir Tchizhov, Head of the Third
Directorate for European Affairs at the Russian Foreign Ministry,
said that "no one expects either side to be satisfied 100
percent about the U.N. document, because whatever the document
or solution, it must come from compromise."
</P>
<P>
The Russian envoy, who arrived here Thursday, said he
exchanged views with President Clerides on all fundamental
aspects of the Cyprus problem and the solution process,
describing the exchange as "very useful and important."
</P>
<P>
After meeting Clerides, Tchizhov crossed into northern Cyprus
where he met Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash.
</P>
<P>
The Russian official noted that the next steps to be taken on
the Cyprus problem will be discussed during the second round of
direct talks between the two sides scheduled to be held on August
11-16 at Montreux, Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the methodology the U.N. has introduced during
the face-to-face talks between President Clerides and Denktash at
Troutbeck, near New York from July 9 to 12, Tchizhov said this
methodology is different from previous ones which he described as
"not very successful."
</P>
<P>
"In the past, the U.N. and successive Secretaries-General
presented documents, noted both sides' observations and then
reported to the Security Council that the chasm remained and
could not be bridged. Now however, negotiations have begun on
specific issues," the Russian official said.
</P>
<P>
Tchizhov noted that the issue of sovereignty is a major
stumbling block to a solution to the Cyprus problem and both
sides on the island held widely divergent views on the issue.
</P>
<P>
However, he did not exclude the possibility that some sort of
agreement can be reached on that sticking point.
</P>
<P>
The Russian envoy also reiterated his government position
that the whole process in Cyprus must continue to develop within
the U.N. framework.
</P>
<P>
The Cyprus issue has remained unresolved since 1974 when the
island was partitioned after Turkish troops took over the
northern third in the wake of a failed coup seeking union with
Greece by some Greek Cypriots. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970718.0036 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Moves to Revitalize Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 18 (Xinhua) -- The Nigerian government will
conclude plans to boost economic growth by the end of this
month, economic observers said here today.
</P>
<P>
To achieve growth, the government is to introduce three
salutary initiatives which are expected to alleviate the present
harsh economic climate and reduce the operating cost of
manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
The measures are an across-the-board improvement in wages, the
gradual release of capital votes and the revaluation of Naira,
the local currency, in a view to cutting the cost of
manufacturers' inputs.
</P>
<P>
The steps are to be taken as the economy turned sluggish in
the first half of this year because of government's tight fiscal
and monetary measures.
</P>
<P>
According to a Finance Ministry source, the reflationary
package planned is to be implemented systematically so that
inflation rate does not shoot up more than what the government
can contain.
</P>
<P>
The government was emboldened by its success in the control of
cash and current account (M1), which grew by 1.7 percent in the
first quarter of this year instead of 15 percent projected.
</P>
<P>
The M1 headroom, according to the source, is in turn to be
used by the government for the planned economic reflation, which
is expected to cause no damage to the macro-economic achievements
characterized by declining inflation rate and stable exchange and
interest rates.
</P>
<P>
Total capital votes for the first half year stand at 44
billion Naira (about 5.2 billion U.S. Dollars). The much-awaited
release will ensure that new contracts are executed and jobs are
created.
</P>
<P>
Agriculture and infrastructure and energy will be the main
focus of government's strategy in its release of capital votes.
</P>
<P>
With the revaluation of Naira, manufacturing companies, which
recorded higher operation costs in the second quarter due to the
devaluation of Naira in March, may be able to access to more
funds to lower the cost.
</P>
<P>
It is also expected to have a mitigating influence on the
inflationary nature of the capital vote release and improvement
in wages.
</P>
<P>
Observers say the increase in wage is expected to improve the
purchasing power of workers, stimulating demand for goods and
services,thus rekindling activities in the manufacturing
sector.
</P>
<P>
As an early reaction to the news of revaluation of the local
currency, export proceeds gained 1.5 Naira in local foreign
exchange markets on Thursday, at a rate of 82 Naira to the U.S.
Dollar. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
