<HEADLINE> Boardman Was Beaten in Time-trial of Tour de France </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, July 18 (Xinhua) -- Chris Boardman of Britain had a
disaster in Friday's 55km time-trial 12th stage of the Tour de
France when the race reached in St Etienne.
</P>
<P>
The world hour record-holder, suffering from a bad back hurt in
a fall three days ago, clocked an unofficial one hour 23 minutes
and eight seconds.
</P>
<P>
He was overtaken on the line by Belgium's Franck Vandenbrouck,
who had started two minutes after him and who took the provisional
lead with another 90 riders, including Tour leader Jan Ullrich,
yet to ride.
</P>
<P>
"It's the first time in five years as a professional I've
finished a time-trial so badly," added Boardman who admitted he
had been taking pain-killers and anti-inflammatories since he fell
in the first stage in the Pyrenees.
</P>
<P>
Boardman started the trial 70 minutes behind Ullrich in 91st
place. 
</P>
