<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japanese Agency Urges Structural Reform for Long-term </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, July 18 (Xinhua) -- Structural reforms in financial
markets and deregulation are essential for the Japanese economy's
long-term growth, the Economic Planning Agency's (EPA) annual
white paper on the economy said today.
</P>
<P>
Japan's potential for long-term economic growth is at risk
unless the government and the private sector accelerate reforms of
its inefficient financial services markets, the white paper
warned.
</P>
<P>
Other non-manufacturing sectors, such as retailing and
construction, should also be liberalized to enhance their
productivity, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
The white paper, submitted by the EPA and adopted by the
cabinet later in the day, said the economy was finally moving
towards recovery after a minor downturn in the summer of 1996.
</P>
<P>
The EPA admitted that the increase in the consumption tax in
April from 3 to 5 percent had slowed down economic activity, but
said this adverse effect "will not have the power to reverse the
trend" (of recovery) and that "after such impact runs its course,
the Japanese economy should regain momentum for a self-reliant
recovery."
</P>
<P>
The paper said, "The problem is how (that dynamism for
recovery) can be linked to sustainable, long-term prosperity."
</P>
<P>
Japan has to overcome many hurdles and the government needs to
implement deregulation and structural reforms in the financial and
non-manufacturing sectors.
</P>
<P>
The financial system is an area where "particularly drastic
reform should be promoted," the paper says.
</P>
<P>
Japan's financial intermediary system -- under a web of
regulations on interest rates, commissions or business sectors --
has failed to provide consumers and corporations with diversified
financial instruments, it says.
</P>
<P>
The report also says that deregulation to promote foreign
investment and to facilitate mergers and acquisitions in Japan
will help improve productivity in the service sector because
newcomers will bring competition through better technologies and
services. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
