<HEADLINE> WB, Japan Give Manila Loans to Expand Freeport </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 18 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank and Japan's Overseas
Economic Cooperation Fund have agreed to give the Philippines huge
loans for the expansion of its Subic Bay Freeport, the Philippine
News Agency said today.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted officials of the Subic Metropolitan Authority
as saying the Subic local government has finalized agreements with
the World Bank and Japan for providing loans.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank will finance 60 million dollars and Japan will
provide 9 million dollars, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
The loan from the World Bank will be used to upgrade water
system, power supply network, road system and other infrastructure
facilities in the Subic Bay Freeport, about 120 kilometers north
of Manila.
</P>
<P>
Japan will help improve the freeport's solid waste management
system and its environmental standards.
</P>
<P>
Under the proposed expansion project, the freeport, a former
United States naval base, will put up more infrastructure in order
to accommodate more businesses.
</P>
<P>
The Subic Metropolitan Authority will soon sign an agreement
with the country's Board of Investments (BOI) to allow businesses
located in the freeport to get more incentives from the
government, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Subic, which has attracted a lot of local and foreign
investments in recent years, is a major economic zone for the
Philippines. 
</P>
</TEXT>
