<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Leone Junta Demand Leader's Release for Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 18 (Xinhua) -- Sierra Leone's military junta
Thursday asked for the release of ex-rebel leader Foday Sankoh as
the first condition for peace, reports said today.
</P>
<P>
It would be impossible to strike a deal without Sankoh, leader
of the Revolutionary United Front (RUF) who has been under
security protection in the Nigerian capital of Abuja since March
this year, said a spokesman of the junta.
</P>
<P>
The RUF, which launched a civil war against successive
governments in Sierra Leone since 1991, entered the capital
Freetown in the wake of the May 25 coup which brought Major
Johnny Koroma to power.
</P>
<P>
It is reported Koroma has included some 6,000 RUF fighters in
his armed forces and named Sankoh the number two man of his
government.
</P>
<P>
"You can't make any peace in Sierra Leone without Foday
Sankoh," said the spokesman, Corporal Tamba Gborie, who
reportedly led the coup that toppled the civilian government led
by President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah.
</P>
<P>
Gborie was in Abidjan, Cote d'Ivoire, with a government
delegation for talks with west African countries on settling the
crisis caused by the coup in Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
The coup, which received wide international condemnation, has
led to military intervention of the sub-regional peacekeeping
force (ECOMOG) led by Nigeria, in a bid to restore Kabbha's
government.
</P>
<P>
Bloody clashes have been reported between ECOMOG and troops
loyal to Koroma, with more than 100 people dead. ECOMOG still
holds some strategic positions in Freetown.
</P>
<P>
Giving another condition for the military to relinquish power,
Gborie said "we are ready to disarm, but we can't (do it) with
Nigeria's bombing our country."
</P>
<P>
The result of the one-day talks is yet to be known but
observers here noted that the conditions of the junta might not
be accepted by the Economic Community of West African States
(ECOWAS) Committee of Four on Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
The Abidjan meeting between the junta and the Committee of
Four was seen as a last option for peaceful settlement of the
Sierra Leonean crisis before a military operation.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970718.0052 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-18 </DATE_TIME>
