<HEADLINE> Iran, Philippines to Strengthen Investment Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 18 (Xinhua) -- Iran, one of the world's biggest
oil producers, has agreed to make major investments in Mindanao,
the southern Philippines, the Philippine Presidential Press Office
said today.
</P>
<P>
A Memorandum of Agreement on investment cooperation was signed
here this morning by Ali Shams Ardekani, secretary general of the
Iranian Chamber of Commerce, Mines and Industry, and Philippine
officials, the office said in a press release.
</P>
<P>
Under the memorandum, Iran agreed to pour investments into
oil-related downstream industries, cement and steel plants in
joint venture with Filipino investors.
</P>
<P>
Iran will build a 150,000 barrel per day oil refinery, a cement
plant, a rolling steel mill and an assembly plant for farm
tractors in Mindanao.
</P>
<P>
President Fidel Ramos, who witnessed the signing of the
document, said the agreement manifested the very effective
partnership that exists between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Mindanao, where the economy has been battered by a long-time
Muslim separatist movement, has attracted large amounts of foreign
investments since last September when a major Muslim rebel group
forged a peace pact with the government.
</P>
<P>
Peace has returned to most parts of Mindanao after the signing
of the peace deal by the rebel Moro National Liberation Front
(MNLF) and Manila last year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
