<DOCNO> XIE19970718.0054 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Southern Africa to Suffer Long Dry Season </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 18 (Xinhua) -- The Southern African Development
Community (SADC) officials said global climatic change may end in
little rains in the region during the 1997/98 crop season.
</P>
<P>
In its latest bulletin released here today, the organization
said events were following a trend frequently associated with dry
years.
</P>
<P>
"Although it is still early to make any definite predictions
concerning the next rainly season... observations of global
climatic data and results of climate forecasting models point to
the possibility of another warm El Nino-Southern Oscillation
(ENSO) occurring during the 1997/98 crop growing season," it
said.
</P>
<P>
Warm episodes have been associated with poor rainfall in
southern Africa.
</P>
<P>
Anomalously warm sea surface temperatures in the eastern
Pacific ocean and the central Indian Ocean through February were
often associated with poor rains in southern SADC, it said.
</P>
<P>
The bulletin said the current developments, which could have
potentially adverse impacts on the 1997/98 crop season, had been
reported as a matter of concern to SADC ministers of food,
agriculture and natural resources.
</P>
<P>
"The drought monitoring center, the regional early warning
system and national meteorological services will continue to
monitor developments closely and will collaborate in providing
further reports in the near future," said the bulletin. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
