<HEADLINE> Beijing Getting Tougher On Audio-Video Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 18 (Xinhua) -- The Beijing municipal legislature
passed a regulation today imposing tougher controls on the
audio-video business in the city.
</P>
<P>
The regulation prevents dealers from getting involved in the
business unless they obtain a certificate, and if they then
violate other parts of the regulations, the certificate will be
revoked.
</P>
<P>
The regulation prohibits release of video and audio products
that disrupt national unity, sovereignty and territorial
integrity, leak state secrets, or are violent, superstitious or
pornographic in nature.
</P>
<P>
It stipulates that home-use video-tapes can not be used for
public shows, as a means of protecting the copyright.
</P>
<P>
The regulations were passed by the Municipal People's Congress
and will take effect next January.
</P>
<P>
The city now has 132 video and audio producers and more than
2,000 shops. Since 1994, some 1.7 million illegal CDs, video
tapes, and cassettes have been confiscated in the city. 
</P>
</TEXT>
