<HEADLINE> Three Union Ministers in India Asked to Resign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, July 18 (Xinhua)-- President of newly formed
Rashtriya Janata Dal and Bihar Chief Minister Laloo Prasad Yadav
today asked his party's three union ministers to resign from the
United Front (UF) government headed by Inder Kumar Gujral.
</P>
<P>
Following the decision not to induct his party into the UF,
Laloo had asked his party's ministers to resign, he told reporters
at his official residence in Bihar state in eastern India.
</P>
<P>
A UF core committee meeting was held here Thursday night and
different views were expressed over the entry of Laloo's party
into the UF.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman of the UF said that the four-hour meeting had
decided to keep the Rashtriya Janata Dal, a split faction from the
Janata Dal on July 5 this year, out of the UF.
</P>
<P>
President of Dravida Munnetra Kazhagam (DMK), a constituent of
the UF, today however said that Thursday evening's meeting did not
decide to keep Laloo's party out of the UF and that the UF
Steering Committee would decide the issue in its July 25 meeting.
</P>
<P>
The Janata Dal, the major constituent of the 13-party UF, was
split into two factions in early July. Laloo Prasad's main rival
Sharad Yadav became new president of the Janata Dal in the July 3
party election while Laloo Prasad and his supporters boycotted the
party election and floated a new party called Rashtriya Janata Dal
on July 5.
</P>
<P>
Before the party's election, Laloo Prasad was its president.
Laloo has time and again said that his new party would continue to
support the UF government in the center.
</P>
<P>
Because of the split, the union ministers belonging to the
Janata Dal were also split into two groups. Coal Minister Kanti
Singh, Non-Conventional Energy Affairs Minister Jai Narayan Nishad
and, Food and Consumer Affairs Minister Raghubans Prasad Singh
support Laloo Prasad.
</P>
<P>
Laloo Prasad told reporters that his party would continue to
support the UF government at the center from outside. Holding
Former Prime Minister Deve Gowda responsible for denying his
party's entry into the front, he charged Gowda with playing into
the hands of communal forces to weaken the secular front.
</P>
