<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Int'l Conference on "One Country, Two Systems" in HK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 18 (Xinhua) -- A two-day international
conference on "one country, two systems", the basic principle of
the Chinese government for Hong Kong after its return to China on
July 1 this year, ended here today.
</P>
<P>
Some 50 law experts from Hong Kong, China's interior areas and
other parts of the world, including lawyers, legislators, judges,
professors and researchers, attended the "One Country, Two
Systems: Theory and Practice" conference at Hotel Furama in
downtown Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
They exchanged views on a wide range of topics, such as the
political, economic and judicial structures of the Hong Kong
Special Administrative Region (HKSAR) after 1997, application of
the HKSAR Basic Law and other Chinese national laws in Hong Kong,
and roles of the HKSAR Chief Executive and Legislative Council.
</P>
<P>
They also discussed human rights and environment protection in
Hong Kong, prospects for cooperation between Hong Kong and China's
interior areas and many other issues.
</P>
<P>
In a special speech this morning, Rita Fan Hsu Lai Tai,
chairwoman of the HKSAR Provisional Legislative Council (PLC),
reviewed the PLC's establishment and its major responsibilities.
</P>
<P>
Since it was elected on December 21 last year, she said, the
60-member PLC has to date passed four bills and adopted 19
motions.
</P>
<P>
Tung Chee Hwa, Chief Executive of the HKSAR, Thursday attended
the opening ceremony of the conference, which was jointly
sponsored by the Center for Chinese and Comparative Law of the
City University of Hong Kong and the Hong Kong-based One Country,
Two Systems Economic Research Institute.
</P>
<P>
Initiated by the late Chinese leader Deng Xiaoping in the
1980s, the concept of "one country, two systems" allows two
different social systems -- socialism and capitalism -- to coexist
and seek common development within one sovereign state.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
