<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Payroll Up in 1st Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 18 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong's average labor
earnings rose by 9.5 percent in nominal terms in the first quarter
of 1997 over a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
The earnings, as measured by payroll per person engaged in all
major business sectors, actually went up by 3.1 percent after
taking inflation into account, according to figures released today
by the Census and Statistics Department.
</P>
<P>
Employees in financing, insurance, real estate and business
sectors saw their payroll growing by 11.7 percent in nominal
terms, or 5.2 percent in real terms, the fastest increases among
all lines of trade.
</P>
<P>
Earnings in wholesale, retail, trade, manufacturing, restaurant
and hotels sectors all climbed up in real terms in the first three
months of this year, while the actual labor earnings in the
transport, storage and communications sectors remained unchanged.
</P>
<P>
Statistics on average payroll are compiled on quarterly basis
by the Census and Statistics Department.  
</P>
</TEXT>
