<HEADLINE> Turkey Sends Warships to N. Cyprus for Celebrations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, July 18 (Xinhua) -- Six Turkish warships arrived at
northern Cyprus this morning for celebrations marking the 23th
anniversary of Turkish intervention in the northern part of the
Mediterranean island.
</P>
<P>
Reports reaching here said two frigates, two speedboats and two
submarines sailed into the port of Girne in an open parade of
Turkey's determination to safeguard the security of Turkish
Cypriots on the divided island,
</P>
<P>
Cyprus was split in 1974 into two communities, with Greek
Cypriots owning two thirds of the island in the south and Turkish
Cypriots, the northern third, in the wake of an abortive
coup seeking union with Greece.
</P>
<P>
Turkey's newly-appointed Deputy Prime Minister Bulent Ecevit,
who in 1974 was the prime minister that ordered Turkish troops to
land on the island, is expected at Sunday's celebrations in
northern Cyprus heading a large delegation.
</P>
<P>
During a meeting with a senior Turkish Cypriot official here
Wednesday, the hardline Turkish leader warned that Turkey's
exclusion from the coming European Union (EU) membership
negotiations would hamper the ongoing direct talks between Greek
and Turkish Cypriot sides sponsored by U.N. Secretary General Kofi
Annan.
</P>
<P>
Ankara was obviously angered by a European Commission agreement
Tuesday to recommend six nations - Cyprus, Poland, the Czech
Republic, Hungary, Slovenia, and Estonia - for the first wave of
EU accession talks.
</P>
<P>
Ecevit threatened that the "discriminative decision" by the
EU's executive body would speed up the integration process of
Turkey and northern Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
The Cyprus issue has long been a thorny problem for the
international community. At present, around 30,000 Turkish troops
remain stationed on the northern third of the island. 
</P>
</TEXT>
