<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ban on Medicine Imports Causes More Deaths in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, July 18 (Xinhua) -- The current ban on the
importation of chloroquine, anti-malaria medicine by the private
sector in Uganda has caused increase of malaria deaths, the local
daily, The New Vision, reported today.
</P>
<P>
Edward Ddumba of the medical department in Mulago Hospital
here was quoted as saying that this week there was no injectable
chloroquine drug in all private clinics in Kampala, following the
ban on its importation by Uganda National Drug Authority (UNDA)
starting in May this year.
</P>
<P>
Noah Lukoda, medical officer of central district of Luwero was
quoted as saying that one of the reasons for the escalation of
malaria in his district is the acute shortage of both injectable
chloroquine and quinine drugs in the private sector.
</P>
<P>
Lukoda said, on the average, private clinics and hospitals
handle 60 percent of the patients in the country. In some places
the percentage is as high as 80 percent.
</P>
<P>
Malaria is the number one killer disease in the country,
contributing 25 percent of deaths.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that chloroquine cannot cure severe malaria
because this kind of malaria is resistant to quinine.
</P>
<P>
Because of low quality of chloroquine imported by the private
sector, UNDA banned its importation.
</P>
<P>
However, chloroquine is still the first line of treatment of
malaria all over the country and doctors can't do without it.
They still put it on the essential drugs list.
</P>
<P>
Due to lack of anti-malaria drugs such as quinine and other
reasons such as movements of displaced persons, an epidemic of
malaria has broken out around Lake Wamala, 60 km west of Kampala.
</P>
<P>
About 150 people in Kapchorwa, eastern Uganda, have been
killed by malaria since May when the UNDA started to ban
importation of quinine by the private sector. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970718.0069 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Korea to Renovate Financial Structure </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Ministry of Finance and Economy said today that the collapse of
the eight-largest conglomerate Kia Group, following Hanbo, Sammi and
Jinro, stemmed from the excessive expansion of its business territory.
</P>
<P>
A series of group insolvencies were mainly due to the transfer of
huge sums of money gained by the group's leading companies to their
affiliates through insider-trading, which eventually leading to the
deterioration of the group's overall capital holdings, the ministry
said.
</P>
<P>
Although the government has limited the money transfer among
affiliates to a certain level through steps to control and prevent
mutual capital investment, most conglomerates are crossing the limits
by stepping laws aside, the ministry added.
</P>
<P>
"Large-scale bankruptcies will considerably be curtailed should
conglomerates improve their financial structure by slimming their debt
ratios and raising their asset proportion," a ministry official said.
</P>
<P>
Despite strong backlashes from business circles, the government has
decided to take a tough stance to ensure the process goes forward with
ways to renovate their financial structure, the official said.
</P>
<P>
In particular, the government plans to scale down the functions of
chairman and planning-coordination offices since they were found to be
meddling in the management of subsidiaries and pave the way in
curtailing tax payments through tax consultations at a group level, he
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
