<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading French Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, July 18 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news items in
leading French newspapers today:
</P>
<P>
Liberation:
</P>
<P>
-- Two hundred kilometers from the Earth, the mission of two
Russian astronauts and their American colleague on board the space
station Mir turned into a catastrophic scenario on Thursday, as an
essential cable disconnected by mistake cut electric supply and put
computers out of service. The team was plunged into darkness for
the 45 minutes when the space station could not be lighted by the
Sun, and reparation work was not expected to be completed within two
days.
</P>
<P>
-- Voters in the Russian city Niji-Novgorod, formerly called
Gorky and now the lighthouse of economic reform in Russia, elected
with a narrow majority of votes on Monday Ivan Skliarov, a reformer,
as its governor to replace Boris Nemtsov, now the number three of
the Kremlin. The election, which drew nationwide attention as a test
of public opinion, also saw a Communist Party candidate, allied with
the far-right Liberal Democratic Party, closely trailing the liberal
candidate in the two rounds of election.
</P>
<P>
Le Figaro:
</P>
<P>
-- The government of Prime Minister Lionel Jospin is expected to
announce next Monday a plan to raise 21 billion francs (3.5 billion
U.S. dollars) of taxes on enterprises in order to reduce the public
deficit to about 3 percent of gross domestic product (GDP). An audit
of public finance is expected to confirm early next week that the
public deficit of France this year would stand at 3.6-3.7 percent of
the GDP, if no measure is taken to cut the deficit.
</P>
<P>
-- The possible ratification by the French Parliament of an
international convention on the protection of primary arts and
objects of art could worry arts collectors. In order to stop the
stealing of an average of 50,000 art objects each year from Africa,
the Middle East and Asia, the convention allows the original owners
to reclaim their properties in a period ranging from three to 50
years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
