<HEADLINE> Beijing Welcomes Japanese Bankers in Infrastructure Construction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 18 (Xinhua) -- Beijing Mayor Jia Qinglin said
here today that he welcomes the Industrial Bank of Japan, Ltd. to
participate in the city's infrastructural construction.
</P>
<P>
During a meeting with Yoh Kurosawa, chairman of the bank's
board of directors, Jia said the Industrial Bank of Japan is an
influential bank with financial strength, and has business around
the world. The bank also has close ties with Beijing, Jia noted.
</P>
<P>
Jia went on to say that his city needs large sums of money in
infrastructural construction which will focus on the supply of
water, electricity, liquefied petroleum gas, and heat as well as
communications and environmental protection. He expressed his hope
that investors both at home and abroad will take part in the
development.
</P>
<P>
Kurosawa expressed great interest in Jia's words, saying that
cooperation should be strengthened to make the capital of China
more beautiful.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, Jia said that hi-tech products have a
ready market, and they are the growth areas that the city has
decided to develop more. And large sums of money are also required,
he added.
</P>
<P>
Kurosawa said that if the projects need money, the Beijing
branch of his bank is "sure to be very busy."
</P>
<P>
The Industrial Bank of Japan, Limited, established in 1902, is
the biggest long-term credit bank in Japan and a large-scale
international commercial bank. The bank has close relations with
China's economic and financial circles. 
</P>
</TEXT>
