<HEADLINE> Coca Cola Adds Life as Australian Stocks Rise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, July 18 (Xinhua) -- The Australian share market ended
the week on an upbeat note, propelled to higher ground by a 10
percent surge in Coca Cola Amatil shares and stronger gold and
resource sectors.
</P>
<P>
At the close of trading, the benchmark all ordinaries index was
14.5 points higher at 2684.2, just off its intra-day high of
2687.5.
</P>
<P>
Turnover was moderate with 321.08 million shares traded worth
738.44 million Australian dollars (546.44 million U.S. dollars),
with rises outnumbering falls 603 to 452.
</P>
<P>
Coca Cola Amatil jumped 1.53 Australian dollars to 16.58
Australian dollars with 2.845 million shares traded in another day
of volatility for the popular soft drink giant.
</P>
<P>
One broker said the sharp rise in Coca Cola Amatil was a
technical correction as the market over-reacted earlier in the
week to analyst recommendations of a downgrade.
</P>
<P>
The all industrials index was 16.9 points higher at 4276.8
while the all resources index added 13.5 points to 1448.3.
</P>
<P>
Industrials outperformed the market, with mining giant BHP up
10 Australian cents to 18.56 Australian dollars, resource giant
Rio Tinto up 24 Australian cents to 21.80 Australian dollars and
mining company WMC rose 21 Australian cents to 7.87 Australian
dollars.
</P>
<P>
The gold index finished 1.3 percent or 16.9 Australian points
higher at 1313.1 while gold bullion closed in Sydney at 319.00
U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Bank stocks were mixed, with the index rising 16.1 points to
4984.6.
</P>
<P>
ANZ bank climbed 20 Australian cents to 10.15 Australian
dollars, NAB rose 12 to 19.38 Australian dollars, Westpac added
two to 7.90 Australian dollars while Commonwealth Bank tumbled
22.9 cents to 16.246 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
Shares in retail group Harvey Norman Holdings dropped 14
Australian cents to 7.50 after it reported sales from its
franchised stores rose 16.7 percent to 902.8 million U.S. dollars
in the fiscal year ending June 30.  
</P>
