<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Consolidates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, July 18 (Xinhua) -- Higher gold prices, a weaker New
Zealand currency and comments by a former Reserve Bank of
Australia (RBA) governor today spurred the Australian dollar to
its firmest close this week.
</P>
<P>
The local unit finished today's trading at 73.89 U.S. cents, up
from 73.67 cents Thursday. It finished just off its afternoon high
of 74.00 U.S. cents and well above its low of 73.37.
</P>
<P>
Rothschild Australia senior manager Mark McCloskey attributed
the Australian dollar's strength to good buying orders and a small
rally in the gold price.
</P>
<P>
Gold closed in Sydney today at 324.00 U.S. dollars per fine
ounce, from Thursday's close of 319.00 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
This afternoon, Bernie Fraser, former RBA governor, said he
believed the RBA had missed an opportunity to cut interest rates
for what would be a fifth time in the past year.
</P>
<P>
"Maybe a few of the offshore people have taken his comments to
heart," McCloskey suggested.
</P>
<P>
On the cross rates, the Australian dollar's most impressive
gain was against the New Zealand dollar which suffered a fall of
just less than one U.S. cent today, following a large sell
overnight order by a U.S. fund.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar also finished at 85.44 Japanese yen, down
from 85.53, and at 1.3244 German marks, down from 1.3252.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
