<DOCNO> XIE19970718.0078 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ramos Hails General Ceasefire Accord with MILF </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 18 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Fidel Ramos
hailed here today the agreement for general cessation of
hostilities signed by the government and the Muslim rebels as a
breakthrough in the peace process in the southern Philippines.
</P>
<P>
"I see this as a big leap towards the attainment of a just and
enduring peace in Mindanao," Ramos said, adding he was confident
that the "breakthrough" agreement will lead to the signing of a
final peace agreement between the government and the Moro Islamic
Liberation Front (MILF).
</P>
<P>
Because of the general ceasefire, Ramos said, the
implementation of vital government projects related to agriculture
and irrigation will be accelerated.
</P>
<P>
The government peace panel led by Fortunato Abat and the MILF
panel headed by vice chairman for political affairs Ghazali Jaafar
signed the general ceasefire agreement earlier today in Cagayan de
Oro city in the southern Philippines.
</P>
<P>
The government and the MILF agreed to commit their respective
forces to a general ceasefire effective on July 21 and direct
their respective sub-committees on ceasefire to meet soon to draw
and finalize the guidelines and rules for the implementation of
the accord.
</P>
<P>
According to the agreement, they also decided to resume and
proceed with the formal peace talks in a venue to be mutually
agreed upon by the two sides.
</P>
<P>
The general ceasefire agreement came unexpectedly after the
MILF warned of a long deadlock in its peace talks with the
government which was stalled by the military's recent offensive
against MILF rebels.
</P>
<P>
A 12,000-member rebel group, the MILF has been fighting
government troops in the southern Philippines. It entered
low-level peace talks with Manila earlier this year, but so far
the two sides have made no substantial progress in forging a peace
agreement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
