<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Reservoirs Release Overflow </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 18 (Xinhua) -- Fifteen of Hong Kong's 17
brimming reservoirs have opened floodgates to release an overflow
after weeks of torrential rains.
</P>
<P>
Entering July, Hong Kong's rainfall has exceeded 600
millimeters, following 780 mm in June and 301 mm in May.
</P>
<P>
Now there are 559.6 million cubic meters of water in storage,
enough for half-year consumption in Hong Kong, according to a
spokesman of the Water Supplies Department. The city consumed 928
million cubic meters of water throughout the year of 1996.
</P>
<P>
Water volume in Hong Kong's largest reservoir, High Island, has
 surged up to 90 percent of its full capacity at the
moment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970718.0086 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Macao Foreign Trade Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, July 18 (Xinhua) -- Both imports and exports for the
first five months of this year increased remarkably in Macao,
latest statistics show.
</P>
<P>
The value of exports between January and May this year reached
6.3 billion patacas (797.47 million U.S. dollars), up 16 percent
from the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
The imports hit 6.8 billion patacas (860.76 million
U.S. dollars), registering an increase of 9 percent.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the trade deficit hit 563 million patacas (71.3
million U.S. dollars), up 34.9 percent from the same period of
last year, according to figures released by the Macao Census and
Statistics Department.
</P>
<P>
The export of textile products and garments, which account for
82.5 percent of all exports, rose 22.7 percent. The proportion of
non-textile product exports dropped a further 4.5 percent,
compared with the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
The United States and the European Union are Macao's major
export markets. The U.S. market bought 38.9 percent of Macao's
exported goods, while the EU absorbed 35.4 percent of Macao's
exports.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Macao imported 20.8 percent more of capital goods,
11.4 percent extra of raw materials and semi-finished products. It
 also imported more fuel and lubricative oil and consumer goods.
</P>
<P>
Those imported goods mainly came from the Asia-Pacific region.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
