<DOCNO> XIE19970718.0089 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Xiaolangdi Dam Project May End Yellow River Dry Spell </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHENGZHOU, July 18 (Xinhua) -- A Chinese hydraulics expert has
predicted that the annual dry spell which occurs in the Yellow
River in the April-June period, a crucial season for crop growth,
will become a rarity once the Xiaolangdi Water-control Project
goes into full operation in 2001.
</P>
<P>
Xiaolangdi, located at the exit of the last gorge of the
river's middle reaches, has a designed water storage capacity of
12.65 billion cubic meters.
</P>
<P>
Once operational, it will be able to collect four billion cubic
meters of water in the winter-spring period and discharge them in
a systematic way for areas in the lower reaches during the dry
season.
</P>
<P>
By then, the irrigated areas along the river are expected to
spread from 739,000 ha to 1.52 million ha.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, some large cities such as Qingdao, Tianjin, Beijing
and water-deficient areas in north China may benefit from the
project.
</P>
<P>
The Yellow River, the second longest in China, has an annual
flow of 58 billion cubic meters of water, nearly half of which has
been used to sustain industrial and agricultural production and
people's everyday life.
</P>
<P>
However, over 60 percent of the river's water flows in the
July-September period each year, causing heavy floods in some
areas. But the April-June period, the high season for water
supply, receives only 20 percent of the annual total.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, drought along the upper reaches have caused
dry stretches at different sections of the waterway.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that in the 25 years up to 1996, the river's
lower reaches have dried up on 19 occasions, bringing about a
direct economic loss of 20 billion yuan for agricultural and
industrial production in the river basin.
</P>
<P>
This year's dry spell was longer and particularly severe, and
has attracted the attention of government officials and experts.
</P>
<P>
An expert in charge of the project said the operation of the
Xiaolangdi multi-purpose dam project would effectively solve this
long-standing problem.
</P>
<P>
In addition, people should economize on water and the central
government should unify the management of the water diversion
program from water-sufficient south China to arid north China, he
said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
