<DOCNO> XIE19970718.0093 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Not To Build More Oil Refineries Around 2000 (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 18 (Xinhua) -- Sinopec, the flagship of China's
petrochemical industry, has announced that it will set up no new
oil refineries in the country for at least the next three years.
</P>
<P>
"We will upgrade our existing enterprises through overall
technological renovation, rather than launching new projects in
the next three years or even early in the next century," Sheng
Huaren, president of the China Petrochemical Corporation
(Sinopec), said in an interview with Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
The reform will help Sinopec reduce its total investment in the
Ninth Five-Year Plan period (1996-2000) to 150 billion yuan (18
billion US dollars), from the previously planned 180 billion yuan,
Sheng said.
</P>
<P>
Sinopec has led the rapid growth of China's petrochemical
industry since its establishment in 1983.
</P>
<P>
The amount of processed crude oil all over the country climbed
to 118 million tons last year, from 70 million tons in 1983.
</P>
<P>
The industry produced 2.45 million tons of ethylene in 1996,
compared with 500,000 tons in 1983.
</P>
<P>
"But domestic petrochemical enterprises have to increase
economic efficiency and enhance their competitiveness since more
and more foreign companies have entered China and made market
competition even more fierce," Sheng said.
</P>
<P>
"Expanding production capacity of old enterprises through
intensive technological renovation has been proved more economical
and efficient than building new ones," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Beijing-based Yanshan Petrochemical Co, for example, has
increased its annual ethylene production capacity from 300,000
tons to 650,000 tons.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the company spent seven billion yuan on the whole
renovation project, compared with more than 16 billion yuan
invested in a 300,000-ton ethylene production line erected in
south China's Guangdong Province in the 1990-1995 period.
</P>
<P>
"We have introduced Yanshan's successful experience to four
other ethylene enterprises," Sheng said, pointing out that each of
them will be capable to increase annual ethylene output to 600,000
tons from the current 300,000 tons after the renovations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970718.0094 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Not To Build More Oil Refineries Around 2000 (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Zhenhai Refinery and Petrochemical Co. in east China's Zhejiang
Province is another successful example of Sinopec's reforms.
</P>
<P>
Zhenhai has saved almost four billion yuan to double its
refining capacity of eight million tons through upgrading
technology and facilities.
</P>
<P>
"Zhenhai will be a model of not only the refinery industry, but
also other petrochemical sectors such as deep processing of
petroleum, chemical fiber and chemical fertilizer production,"
Sheng noted.
</P>
<P>
He said Sinopec's total investment in technological renovation
will surpass that of capital construction during the 1996-2000
period.
</P>
<P>
In the interview, Sheng also mentioned cooperation with foreign
companies in jointly setting up advanced and large petrochemical
projects.
</P>
<P>
"We are negotiating with some big foreign firms and planning to
join hands in establishing 600,000-ton ethylene projects at
Nanjing, Shanghai, Lanzhou and Tianjin cities and in Fujian
Province," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
