<HEADLINE> Australia, ROK To Talk Over Trade, Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, July 18 (Xinhua) -- Australia and the Republic of
Korea (ROK) are scheduled to hold a high-level economic meeting
here next week in a bid to boost their trade and economic ties.
</P>
<P>
The Fourth Annual Joint Economic Committee Meeting between
Australia and the Republic of Korea will be held on July 21-22,
according to a statement released here today by Australia's
Department of Foreign Affairs and Trade.
</P>
<P>
The talks are expected to cover key subjects of mutual
interest, including cooperation in APEC, WTO and OECD, trade and
investment promotion, access to the South Korean and Australian
markets, possible joint ventures in third countries and
cooperation in industry, science, technology and natural
resources.
</P>
<P>
The joint committee is an important component of a growing
range of bilateral meetings between Australia and the ROK covering
trade, aid, civil aviation, energy, security, nuclear policy and
United Nations issues, said the statement.
</P>
<P>
The Australian delegation will be led by Penny Wensley, acting
deputy secretary of the Department of Foreign Affairs and Trade,
while the South Korean delegation will be led by Hong Jung Pyo,
deputy minister for economic affairs of the South Korean Ministry
of Foreign Affairs.
</P>
<P>
The ROK is Australia's third largest trading partner and second
largest export market.
</P>
<P>
Australian exports to the ROK have been growing at an annual
rate of 18 percent on the average over the past 15 years.
</P>
<P>
There has also been rapid expansion of tourism and education
links between the two countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
