<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Korea Regrets Over U.S. Anti-Dumping Measures </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, July 18 (Xinhua) -- South Korea today expressed regret
over the decision of the United States not to revoke its
anti-dumping measures on South Korean-made 16 mega-D ram chips and
threatened to bring the case to the World Trade Organization (WTO).
</P>
<P>
Foreign Ministry spokesman Lee Kyu-hyung said that his
government felt regretful over the decision of the U.S. Department
of Commerce to "employ the arbitrary factor of the possibility of
future dumping in order not to revoke the anti-dumping measures
against South Korean semiconductors".
</P>
<P>
The spokesman noted that South Korean chips have already met
the requirements for the revocation of the anti-dumping measures
when the U.S. authorities recently announced the dumping rate for
South Korean chipmakers LG and Hyundai at less than 0.5 percent
for the third consecutive year.
</P>
<P>
"South Korean government will take appropriate measures such as
suing the U.S. at the WTO on the issue," said the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
Ministry officials said that the filing will take place as soon
as possible in consultations with related ministries.
</P>
<P>
In a similar case, South Korea has filed early this month a
complaint with the WTO, demanding the U.S. lift anti-dumping
measures against South Korean color-television sets. 
</P>
</TEXT>
