<HEADLINE> 16 Hamas Members Arrested by Israel Security Forces </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 18 (Xinhua) -- Israeli security forces have
arrested 16 members of the militant Islamic Resistance Movement
(Hamas) allegedly responsible for several terror attacks in the
West Bank, Israel Radio reported today.
</P>
<P>
The Hamas cell was uncovered by Israel's secret security
apparatus General Security Service (GSS) in a recent operation,
the report said.
</P>
<P>
The Hamas cells' attacks along the Trans-West Bank highway had
wounded two Israeli soldiers and four civilians, an Israeli army
sources was quoted as saying. The cell members reportedly also
planned to steal weapons from Israeli soldiers and settlers for
future attacks.
</P>
<P>
Most of their attacks involved boobytrapping Israeli
installations, such as equipment belonging to Israeli electric and
telecommunications companies, and then setting off bombs when
Israeli soldiers and technicians arrived.
</P>
<P>
Following interrogation, Israeli security agents located a
large amount of homemade explosives. One member of the cell was
suspected of planting a pipe bomb earlier this year in a garbage
can in Petah Tikva, near Tel Aviv, which failed to explode.
</P>
<P>
The cell began operation in 1993, and its members, mainly
involved in disturbances, had been jailed for such activities in
the past. After their release in 1995, they resumed anti-Israeli
activities and even recruited more members into the group.
</P>
<P>
Israeli troops have reportedly been put under special alert
amid rumors that Palestinian extremists may try to kidnap Israeli
soldiers to win the release of three Palestinian policemen
captured early this week by Israeli army.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli army said the policemen were arrested Monday night
on their way to carry out a shooting attack against a Jewish
settlement near the West Bank city Nablus. This incident sparked
loud protests from Israeli government which accused the
Palestinian National Authority (PA) of organizing terror attacks
against Israel.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu dispatched Wednesday
GSS head Ami Ayaalon to Gaza to meet PNA President Yasser Arafat
on the arrest of the Palestinian policemen. Israel is reportedly
demanding Arafat take steps to prevent the re-occurrence of such
incidents. 
</P>
</TEXT>
