<HEADLINE> S. African Businessmen to Visit Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 18 (Xinhua) -- A broad-based South African trade
delegation, led by South African Deputy Minister of Trade and
Industry P. Mlambo-Ngcuka and Deputy Minister of Agriculture A.T.
Didiza, will visit Kenya from July 24 to 26.
</P>
<P>
The delegation is expected to visit Tanzania and Uganda first,
local reports said today.
</P>
<P>
The delegates are from South Africa's top-level industrial
organizations and some 35 companies respectively in stationery,
diesel engines, telephone and fibre optic cables, financial
services, packaging, construction equipment, food products,
agro-processing, pharmaceutical equipment and so on.
</P>
<P>
Kenya is South Africa's largest African trade partner outside
the Southern African Development Community and recognized as the
hub of the eastern African market.
</P>
<P>
Their bilateral trade totaled 240 million U.S. Dollars last
year.
</P>
<P>
Kenya's exports to South Africa shot up by 300 percent from
1994 to 1996 while South Africa's exports to Kenya jumped by 45
percent. 
</P>
