<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing Opens First Air-Conditioned Bus Route </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 18 (Xinhua) -- Beijing opened its first
air-conditioned bus route today running between downtown Qianmen
and the Summer Palace, a tourist attraction in the northwestern
suburbs.
</P>
<P>
The Number 808 city bus will, for the first time in Beijing's
history, offer a cool ride for passengers tired of the stifling
heat in this northern Chinese city, which is known for its
scorching summers and ice-cold winters.
</P>
<P>
"It is a bus route to cater to passengers of different
incomes," said Zheng Shusen, general manager of the Beijing Public
Traffic Corporation.
</P>
<P>
The new bus line, comprised of 25 domestic-built buses, will
start its route at 7 a.m. and end at 8:30 p.m., with stops at 13
stations, Xuanwumen, Xidan, the Beijing Zoo, the People's
University and Zhongguancun.
</P>
<P>
The ticket fair is a little bit higher than that for ordinary
buses in Beijing, but is almost the same as the price for
privately or collectively owned mini-buses, ranging from two
to six yuan, or around 24 to 72 US cents.
</P>
<P>
According to Zheng, another three to four air-conditioned bus
routes will be opened in the near future, with a total of 130
air-conditioned buses. 
</P>
</TEXT>
