<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kabila's Troops Drive Ugandan Refugees on Move </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, July 18 (Xinhua) -- Officials of the Democratic
Republic of Congo have ordered tens of thousands of Ugandan
refugees camped across the border to either return to Uganda or
be shifted to refugee camps inside Congo for security reasons.
</P>
<P>
A report reaching here today said Ugandan refugees numbering
up to 35,000 who were sheltered at Kamango in Congo have been
told to shift to other refugee centers further inside Congo or
return to Uganda.
</P>
<P>
Scott Myhre, doctor of World Harvest Mission -- an American
non- governmental organization working in Bundibugyo, western
Uganda, was quoted as saying all the Congo refugee centers are
already overcrowded and it's dangerous to move additional people
into them, adding that conditions are primitive in most of Congo
following years of neglect and the war that ousted former
president of Zaire Mobutu Sese Seko.
</P>
<P>
He said most of the Ugandan refugees are reluctant to go to
the Congolese camps and have started returning home.
</P>
<P>
On June 16, 1997, rebels of the Allied Democratic Forces
suddenly raided and overran Uganda's west district of Bundybugyo
bordering Congo, forcing tens of thousands of Ugandans run to
neighboring Congo as refugees. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
