<DOCNO> XIE19970718.0114 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russian Defense Council Secretary on Army Reforms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 17 (Xinhua) -- The latest decrees signed by
Russian President Boris Yeltsin are aimed at readjusting the
structure of the armed forces, cutting spendings and paving way
for further military reforms, Defense Council secretary Yuri
Baturin said today.
</P>
<P>
Explaining to the press, Baturin said that Russia will abolish
the general command of the army and replace it with the Defense
Ministry's army headquarters and combat readiness headquarters.
Both headquarters will be led by a vice defense minister.
</P>
<P>
The move is not an army reshuffle, Baturin said. It's only a
change in the commanding system of the armed forces.
</P>
<P>
He explained that the functions of the army's general command
and those of the Headquarters of the General Staff were somewhat
overlapped.
</P>
<P>
On the institutional reforms of the Defense Ministry, Baturin
said after streamlining, the staff of the ministry institutions
will not surpass 1 percent of the total personnel of the armed
forces.
</P>
<P>
By the year 1999, the personnel of the armed forces will be
reduced to 1.2 million, he said, adding 20,000 servicemen will be
reduced this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
