<HEADLINE> Xinhua International News Summary at 0800 GMT, July 18 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL -- Red Cross delegates from the Democratic People's
Republic of Korea and South Korea will meet in Beijing on July 23
to handle the South's direct delivery of the second batch of
private-level food aid to the North. Kang Young-hoon, Chairman of
the South Korean National Red Cross (KNRC), told his North
counterpart over the phone on Friday that the KNRC agreed on the
time and the venue for the talks.
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- NATO's eastward expansion has not solved existing
problems, but created new ones, Russian Prime Minister Viktor
Chernomyrdin said here on Thursday. The military bloc's expansion
into Eastern Europe has turned the plan to change its military and
political structures and its strategic conception into something
in the distant future, Chernomyrdin told the Interfax news agency
before leaving for Brussels.
</P>
<P>
VIENNA -- Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat accused Israeli
Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu of lacking sincerity and wanting
to destroy the Middle East peace process. In an interview with the
Austrian daily newspaper Die Presse published on Thursday, Arafat
said, "Netanyahu does not want peace; on the contrary he is
destroying the peace process." The Palestinian leader, who visited
Austria Tuesday and Wednesday, also condemned Israel's recent
arrest of Palestinian policemen, saying such an act violated the
autonomy accord.
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The United States is sending former congressman
Stephen Solarz to Asia as a special envoy on a mission for a
resolution to the recent Cambodia crisis, the State Department
said on Thursday. Solarz will visit China, Japan, Thailand,
Indonesia, Malaysia and Cambodia, State Department spokesman
Nicholas Burns told reporters.
</P>
<P>
BELGRADE -- An explosion occurred Wednesday night near a base
of the Multinational Stabilization Force (SFOR) in the Bosnian
Serb-controlled town of Banja Luka, SFOR command in southwestern
Bosnia said on Thursday. The explosion was caused by three hand
grenades thrown at the SFOR base and no one was seriously injured,
the Tanjug news agency reported. 
</P>
