<HEADLINE> Local Leaders Vows To Promote Ethical Progress: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 18 (Xinhua) -- The People's Daily, China's
leading newspaper, published full page of speeches by local and
department leaders on their plans to further promote cultural and
ethical progress.
</P>
<P>
These speeches were delivered on July 15 as part of a
teleconference during which the Central Committee for Guiding
Ethical and Cultural Development urged the whole country to engage
in more civil language and deeds, and paying more attention to the
clean environment, good service, and orderly traffic.
</P>
<P>
This new round in the country's drive to promote courtesy is
considered an important move for welcoming the 15th National
Congress of the Chinese Communist Party to be held later this year.
</P>
<P>
The following are excerpts of the speeches by local and
department leaders published today on the People's Daily:
</P>
<P>
-- Li Zhijian, deputy Party chief of Beijing Municipality, said
the Chinese capital will continue to focus on improving the urban
environment, encouraging courtesy and forming new habits in the
whole society.
</P>
<P>
Beijing is one of the key cities chosen for this "heeding
courtesy" drive.
</P>
<P>
Li said that from the end of last year to the Spring Festival,
the public were mobilized to clean more than 6,000 dirty and
unsanitary places in both downtown and suburban areas; and before
July 1 when Hong Kong was returned to China, another 2,075 streets
and 661 neighborhoods were also further cleaned.
</P>
<P>
He pledged that before the National Day on October 1, the city
will work to inspire a helpful attitude among those employees in
the service sector, upgrade the general moral and ethical
standards, and maintain a clean environment.
</P>
<P>
-- Meng Jianzhu, deputy Party chief of Shanghai, said that the
city's major goal for the current drive is to develop a good image
as a cosmopolitan city.
</P>
<P>
His measures include prohibition of vulgar language and
popularization of courteous language, setting standards and rules
for the service sector, and holding contests on relevant knowledge.
</P>
<P>
-- Li Jianguo, deputy Party chief of Tianjin, said that a
series of educational campaigns will be launched to raise the
public awareness of courtesy and more will be invested to improve
the urban environment.
</P>
<P>
-- An official from south China's city of Guangzhou said they
will mainly center efforts on combating corruption in Party and
government administrative departments and unethical market
practices, so as to better the city's overall cultural and ethical
development.
</P>
<P>
-- Officials from the city of Chengdu in Sichuan Province,
Xi'an of Shaanxi Province, Xiamen of Fujian Province and Dalian of
Liaoning Province also explained their respective plans.
</P>
<P>
-- The Central Committee of the Chinese Communist Youth League
said that as part of the ongoing drive, it will continue to
organize the "Young Volunteers" to spend two hours a week on the
improvement of the environment across the country.
</P>
<P>
-- The Ministry of Construction pledged to invest more in the
urban infrastructure in all cities and to strengthen management
over public transportation and living quarters in both the urban
and rural areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
