<HEADLINE> Kenya Protests over U.S. Visit Restriction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 18 (Xinhua) -- Kenya has made a formal protest
to the U.S. administration for placing a quarantine on U.S.
citizens wishing to travel to the eastern African country, citing
insecurity.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. claim that "the existing" chaos make Kenya an unsafe
destination is not true and aims at tarnishing the image of the
country, Kenyan Foreign Minister Stephen Kalonzo Musyoka was
quoted by today's Kenya Times as saying.
</P>
<P>
The situation here is back to normal and tourists, investors
and other entrepreneurs should go about their business normally,
Musyoka urged Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Kenyan government has taken steps to facilitate dialogue
with the opposition and the "disturbances" witnessed here
recently will not recur, he assured.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Musyoka took a swipe at some western correspondents
based in Nairobi for being agents of chaos in their coverage of
riots that rocked parts of the country from May to July.
</P>
<P>
He called on foreign media in Kenya to be non-partisan in
their reporting and reflect the right picture of what was going
on and to stop soiling the image of Kenya.
</P>
<P>
Bloody images in the foreign media of the recent violence in
Kenya is scaring away western tourists, many of them having
canceled their bookings, sources from the Kenya Association of
Tour Operators said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
