<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila Describes Currency Crisis As Region-Wide </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 18 (Xinhua) -- The currency crisis which marred
the local financial market is not only happening in the
Philippines but a region-wide phenomenon, Philippine Finance
Secretary Roberto de Ocampo said here today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a public forum, de Ocampo said the crisis started
from Thailand and is also now being felt in Southeast Asian
countries like Indonesia and Malaysia besides the Philippines.
</P>
<P>
He also traced the problem to the United States stock market,
which became so attractive to investors that big volume of dollar
transfers were pulled out of the Southeast Asia region over the
past months.
</P>
<P>
But meanwhile, de Ocampo denied reports that the Philippine
peso is overvalued, saying the crisis actually started from the
outside, such as the devaluation of the Thai baht before the
turmoil of the Manila financial market.
</P>
<P>
However, he admitted that the true lesson here is that the
local economy must be made stable because no country can avoid
this kind of situation in the international financial market with
a weak economy.
</P>
<P>
On the same day, an expert from the University of the
Philippines' School of Economics also echoed de Ocampo's
sentiments by hailing the government for resorting to the
depreciation of the peso against the U.S. dollar.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
