<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Assures Golan Settlers to Stay </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 18 (Xinhua) -- On the 30th anniversary of
Israel's occupation of Golan Heights, Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu assured Jewish settlers that they would remain
there for years to come.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a celebration held Thursday night in Katzrin to
mark the anniversary, Netanyahu told the settlers that the future
of Golan Heights was tied to the future of the state of Israel.
</P>
<P>
The Jewish state took Golan Heights from Syria during its third
war with Arab countries which started on June 5, 1967.
</P>
<P>
In a bid to justify Israel's continued occupation, Netanyahu
noted that Golan Heights had been ruled by the Jews during
periods in ancient times.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu's statements signaled that he would remain tough on
the issue.
</P>
<P>
Since assuming power last year, the Netanyahu-led Likud
government has made it clear that it would never abandon the whole
Golan Heights in future peace negotiations with Syria.
</P>
<P>
The opposition Labor leader Ehud Barak, who also attended the
ceremony, was booed by the residents when he said that he would
consider Israel's concessions in talks with Syria.
</P>
<P>
But Barak stressed that he would not do so before making sure
that Syria reaches agreement with Israel on the crucial issues of
early-warning stations, water and normalization of ties.
</P>
<P>
Israel's previous Labor government, during its talks with
Syria, had promised a total withdrawal from Golan Heights if Syria
reaches agreements on security arrangements to guarantee Israel's
safety and agrees to sign a peace treaty.
</P>
<P>
Their talks, with a breakthrough in sight, came to an abrupt
stop in early March last year when the Likud was brought to power
in the Israeli elections.
</P>
<P>
Syria has been demanding that the talks be resumed from the
point where they were left off, which means the Likud government
must continue committed to the promise made by its predecessor.
</P>
<P>
This was flatly by the Netanyahu government, which called for
the resumption of the talks without setting any prior conditions.
</P>
<P>
The prolonged deadlock in the peace process has led to rising
tension between the two countries, and Israel has repeatedly
charged that Syria is prepared to launch a surprise attack aimed
at reaping diplomatic gains so as to pressure Israel back to the
negotiating table. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
