<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Exporters Call for Government's Help </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 18 (Xinhua) -- The Board of Trade of Thailand has
urged the government to speed up implementation of the measures it
announced earlier to help exporters, who are affected by the
baht's float.
</P>
<P>
The call was made by representatives from the private sector
when they met senior officials of government departments concerned
on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, Piyabutre Cholvijarn, a Board of Trade
representative and also president of the Union Bank of Bangkok,
said the government's baht float has affected all local industries
and has resulted in an increase in inflation, production costs,
transport fees, and has stalled foreign investment.
</P>
<P>
The measures announced earlier by the government include the
government's 20 billion baht (678 million US dollar) special fund
carrying an 8 percent interest rate, a tax reduction on imported
raw materials and a reduction in the rate of corporate income tax
for exporters.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting, a representative of the National Economic and
Social Development Board said that as Thailand's economic growth
has been primarily export-driven, the board, which is a national
planning agency, recommended that the export sector receive the
helping hand first.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
