<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa Anticipates El Nino-Triggered Drought </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNEBSURG, July 18 (Xinhua) -- South African experts this
week voiced concern about the early build-up of the El Nino
weather phenomenon, which could spark a devastating drought in
the region next year.
</P>
<P>
Two years of soaking rains have given rise to the best crops
in years in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
But a severe El Nino, which has the potential to cause drought
in the region, would cut short the profits from this bumper run,
a local daily The Star reported today.
</P>
<P>
"The Pacific El Nino has developed much earlier than its usual
December arrivals and hits full steam in about January, but it is
up to full strength right now," said Mark Jury, a weather
specialist at the University of Zululand.
</P>
<P>
This century's worst El Nino hit in 1982 and 1983, sparking
hurricanes, droughts, fires and flooding in more than 15
countries.
</P>
<P>
South African government this week issued a warning that an El
Nino was on the way.
</P>
<P>
Kit le Clus, director of the National Maize Producers'
Organization, said the early appearance of El Nino created
worries over next year's maize crop, the country's biggest
agricultural commodity.
</P>
<P>
"The probability of less-than-normal maize production next
year is very strong," he noted.
</P>
<P>
Weather analysts said that in Southern Africa the impact of El
Nino would be felt hardest in Botswana, due to the development in
summer of a high pressure cell over that country.
</P>
<P>
It would then spread out affecting the northern, central and
eastern parts of South Africa and Zimbabwe, they added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
