<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ukrainian Gas Firm Face Financial Problems </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, July 17 (Xinhua) -- The Ukrainian Tax Administration has
recently frozen the largest state gas company Ukrgazprom's bank
accounts because it owes more than 493 million hryvnas (about 274
million U.S. dollars) in taxes.
</P>
<P>
Speaking before a parliamentary session, Ukrgazprom President
Bogdan Kliuk said his company had incurred late payment fines of
284 million hryvnas (about 156 million U.S. dollars) on its 535
hryvnas (294 million dollars) debt to the state.
</P>
<P>
He linked Ukrgazprom's financial troubles to payment
delinquency by gas consumers, noting the private consumers, state
companies and municipal services have run up a 1.9 billion hryvnas
(more than 1 billion dollars) debt to Ukrgazprom for gas supplied
this year.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the rate of payment by customers is worsening,
falling from 83 percent in 1995 to only 15.6 percent this year,
Kliuk said, adding that consumers still owe 2.8 billion hryvnas
(1.5 billion dollars) for gas supplied in 1995 and 1996.
</P>
<P>
Ukrgazprom's lack of funds is not only holding up tax payments,
but is threatening future gas supplies to consumers, Kliuk
warned. The company is now short of cash to buy chemicals it uses
to add an odor to gas. Without these chemicals, it will be
impossible to continue supplies to consumers.
</P>
<P>
Kliuk called for a 20 to 30 percent cut in national gas
consumption and cited figures from other European countries and
around the world to support his claim that Ukrainians burn too
much gas.
</P>
<P>
He said natural gas accounts for 45.5 percent of the country's
fuel needs. In most European countries this figure is between 30
and 35 percent, and in the rest of the world only 21 percent.
</P>
<P>
Ukrgazprom supplied 15.5 billion cubic meters of gas worth 2.4
billion hryvnas (about 1.3 billion dollars) to consumers in the
first half of this year. Annual consumption in Ukraine is around
86 billion cubic meters, 79 percent of which is imported, said
Kliuk. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
