<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Debt Problem Eased in Shanghai's State Sector </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, July 18 (Xinhua) -- The state sector in Shanghai,
once plagued by staggering debt and poor economic efficiency, has
gradually worked its way out of financial difficulty, a municipal
government official said.
</P>
<P>
The state enterprises have managed to reduce their debt ratio to
60 percent this year from the 80 percent three years ago, the
official said.
</P>
<P>
A major reason for the eased debt problem is a redistribution
and more effective use of the state assets, he said.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that about 800 state enterprises had been
merged by the end of last year and another 58 have gone bankrupt,
writing off about 2.63 billion yuan in bad debt reserve funds.
</P>
<P>
"How to reduce the debt ratio of the state sector is one of the
thorniest problems in the restructuring of state enterprises, but
we are getting more confident in the future with all the feasible
solutions in hand," the official said.
</P>
<P>
He added that a modern enterprise system is being introduced
into the state sector to make it more competitive.
</P>
<P>
He revealed that Shanghai will take more measures to reform the
state sector in the second half of this year.
</P>
<P>
Official data show that the industrial sector in Shanghai has
been growing at an annual rate of over 14 percent this year, with the
sales ratio reaching 98 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
