<DOCNO> XIE19970718.0132 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China, U.S. Sign Information Superhighway Education Accord </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 17 (Xinhua) -- China and the United States
today signed an agreement for joint preparation and delivery of a
series of continuing education courses in China on the theory and
practice of the information superhighway.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was signed by Guan Zhicheng, Vice President of
Tsinghua University and William L. Flinn, President and Executive
Director of Midwest Universities Consortium for International
Activities, Inc. (MUCIA) at the Capitol Hill in Washington D.C.
</P>
<P>
The courses will focus on two levels. The first group of
courses will be designed for advanced levels for graduate
engineers and others who wish to gain knowledge pertaining to the
evolving electronic network in China.
</P>
<P>
The second group will be a popular program providing
introductory information to be presented nation-wide through
China's educational television network.
</P>
<P>
The project, the first of several programs to be implemented by
the Chinese government under the Golden Bridges Project, calls for
MUCIA and Tsinghua to design a series of video tape courses.
</P>
<P>
The video courses will be produced by MUCIA member universities
and will be companied with textbook and other instructional
materials.
</P>
<P>
The project will be funded by corporate sponsorships from among
leading U.S. and international technology firms, focusing
particularly on those having a strong interest in China.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the signing ceremony, Guan Zhicheng said, the
project will help bring thousands of Chinese people into the
information era of the 21st century and will promote the reform of
higher education in China.
</P>
<P>
Flinn expressed the hope that the project will contribute to
the relationship between the peoples of the United States and
China as well as to the cooperation between universities of the
two nations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
