<HEADLINE> Direct Telecom Services Across Taiwan Straits Feasible </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, July 18 (Xinhua) -- Post and telecom operations in
Fujian, located across the Taiwan Straits, can be linked with
their Taiwan counterparts just as soon as the time is right,
according to Shangguan Qiwen, director of the Fujian Provincial
Posts and Telecom Administration.
</P>
<P>
The director even outlined a detailed program for the direct
services, which are currently not up for consideration by the
Taiwan authorities.
</P>
<P>
According to the program, postal ships in the future can
shuttle between Fujian, and Mazu and Jinmen.
</P>
<P>
In the realm of telecom services, both parties can make use of
microwave equipment or lay an submarine optic cable to connect
Xiamen with Jinmen.
</P>
<P>
Or, the two sides can open satellite telecom services via a
transporter either in a domestic satellite or in an international
telecom satellite. Fuzhou or Xiamen, each with a ground station,
thus can be linked with Taipei, which also has one station.
</P>
<P>
Shangguan believes the rapid development in the telecom sector
over the past years has laid a solid foundation for the future
direct services. The telephone switching capacity in the province
has hit more than four million lines. And the local mobile telecom
networks now can provide services for hundreds of thousands of
users and the paging networks have 2.6 million users.
</P>
<P>
Some 34 optical cables have been laid in the province with a
total length of more than 10,000 kilometers. Following the Xiamen
satellite ground station, another station is slated to open this
year in Fuzhou, the provincial capital. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
