<HEADLINE> PNG Peace Talks End in New Zealand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, July 18 (Xinhua) -- Representatives from warring
factions of Bougainville Island voiced their desire today to work
together for peace on the war-torn island in Papua New Guinea.
</P>
<P>
The representatives, meeting at Burnham camp in New Zealand's
South Island city of Christchurch for the past two weeks,
expressed the desire in the "Burnham Declaration" they signed this
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
They believe that all sides now have a common will to see an
end to the civil war ranging on the cooper-rich island since 1988.
</P>
<P>
Satisfied with the results of the NZ-brokered talks, NZ Foreign
Minister Don Mckinnon said the declaration is a very strong
foundation on which a peace strategy can be pursued.
</P>
<P>
"I'm pretty satisfied that they are heading in the right
direction, but this is still the first step in bringing the
Bougainville people together."
</P>
<P>
He envisaged another, smaller group representing the factions
will need to meet again before the PNG government joins the
discussions.
</P>
<P>
But it has yet to be decided if New Zealand will continue to be
the venue of future talks.  
</P>
</TEXT>
