<HEADLINE> Jiang Zemin Meets Japan's LDP Secretary-General </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 18 (Xinhua) -- Chinese President Jiang Zemin said
today that both Chinese and Japanese, especially statesmen of the
two countries, should learn from events in history and work
together for the development of sound and stable bilateral
relations in the future.
</P>
<P>
Jiang, also general secretary of the Chinese Communist Party
Central Committee, made the remark here this morning when meeting
with Kato Koichi, secretary-general of Japan's Liberal Democratic
Party (LDP).
</P>
<P>
Extending a welcome to Kato and the LDP delegation, Jiang said
that this year is the 25th anniversary of the normalization of
Sino-Japanese diplamatic relations, and that China is willing to
join hands with Japan's ruling party and Japanese friends from
all walks of life to safeguard and develop the sort of bilateral
friendly situation that is not easy to come by.
</P>
<P>
China is also willing to make joint efforts with the Japanese
friends to build more effective Sino-Japanese relations for the
next century, so as to make greater contributions to the peace,
stability and development in Asia and the world at large, he added.
</P>
<P>
As the history cannot be changed, he pointed out, the past may
be used as a mirror with which to closely examine what has
happened.
</P>
<P>
To correctly understand the past and summarize historical
lessons are conducive to an accurate understanding of the
development trend of the future, and will help to create a better
future for bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
Agreeing with Jiang on his repeated comment that "an overturned
cart ahead is a warning to carts behind," Kato noted that Japan
will persist in taking the route of peaceful development and stick
to a foreign policy of peace.
</P>
<P>
Kato said, "We shall redouble our efforts for a friendly
relationship for the future to be forged by younger generations of
the two countries."
</P>
<P>
Extending congratulations again on China's resumption of the
exercise of its sovereignty over Hong Kong, Kato sincerely hoped
that the great concept of "one country, two systems" will succeed.
</P>
<P>
Jiang expressed his appreciation for Kato's remarks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
