<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India's Private Firms Allowed to Own Satellites </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, July 18 (Xinhua)-- India's union government has
ended state monopoly of satellite usage and ownership by allowing
private firms to use Insat transponders and permitting them to own
satellites, official sources said here today.
</P>
<P>
Under a new policy of the government, Indian private companies
will be allowed to own and operate satellites for which the
Department of Telecommunications will facilitate allocation of
frequencies.
</P>
<P>
Private Indian satellites will be treated as national
satellites and will enjoy the country's protection in terms of
orbital slots. The union government will register these satellites
with the International Telecommunication Union (ITU).
</P>
<P>
The new policy, which was approved by the union cabinet last
week, also allows operations of foreign satellites from Indian
soil in terms of satellite control and unlinking/down linking. But
Indian satellites will be accorded preferential treatment. This
means that Indian satellites, Insats, will have the first right to
choose frequencies.
</P>
<P>
It is expected that the new policy will lead to the development
of a healthy and thriving communications satellite and ground
equipment industry as well as satellite communications service
industry in India, the Indian Space Research Organization said in
a statement.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
