<HEADLINE> Drought Threatens Thailand's Farming </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 18 (Xinhua) -- Drought is threatening large areas
of farmland in Thailand as seasonal rains are late in coming.
</P>
<P>
Crops such as sugarcane, maize and soybean have been hard hit
by the unseasonable long dry spell.
</P>
<P>
More than 640,000 hectares of farmland in 22 provinces, in
particular in the north and northeast, have been affected,
according to Agriculture Ministry officials.
</P>
<P>
The rainy season normally starts in May, but this year the dry
spell has been prolonged and normal rainfall is not expected until
August in many areas.
</P>
<P>
The ministry has told farmers to postpone their first rice crop
planting until August.
</P>
<P>
It has also sought 594 million baht (20 million U.S. dollars)
for emergency relief.
</P>
<P>
The money would be used to buy seeds, fertilizer and pesticide
for farmers stricken by the lack of seasonal rains.
</P>
<P>
As a result of crop damage, maize output this year could be 20
percent below projection, a Commerce Ministry official said. And
sugarcane output would be 10 percent below target, an industry
source estimated.
</P>
<P>
However, it is hoped that the crop damage could be compensated
by replanting or by a second cropping, when rainfall becomes
regular and sufficient.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
