<HEADLINE> India Negotiates WB Loan for AIDS Control </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, July 18 (Xinhua)-- India is negotiating with the
World Bank (WB) for a second loan to continue the fight against
the deadly disease of AIDS, a government official said here today.
</P>
<P>
India received WB's first loan of 87 million U.S. dollars in
1992 to combat AIDS.
</P>
<P>
When the WB project had been launched in 1992, AIDS had mostly
been confined to cities. The second loan will be used primarily to
launch prevention and control activities in the rural areas where
AIDS has now fast spread, he said.
</P>
<P>
Some reports said that India's AIDS patient numbers are the
largest among the developing countries, but the government has
denied the report. There has been no exact figure of AIDS patients
available in the country.  
