<HEADLINE> Ukraine's Population Declines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, July 17 (Xinhua) -- Ukraine's population has dropped by
2.3 percent to 50.2 million this year from 52 million in 1991, a
government official said today.
</P>
<P>
Accordingly, the average life expectancy for Ukrainians has
shortened by 3.5 years. The average life span is 61.2 years for
men and 62.7 years for women, according to Nikolai Soldatenko,
head of the Social Security Department under the Economy Ministry.
</P>
<P>
The population will be further reduced by 4 million by 2026, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Public Health Minister Andrei Serdiuk attributed the population
reduction mainly to infectious diseases and insufficient fund for
residents to get medicines.
</P>
<P>
Some 8.5 million people were registered suffering from
infectious diseases, he said.
</P>
<P>
Within the next 30 years, the number of children under the age
of 15 will decrease by some 3 million and constitute only 16.8
percent of the population, compared with 21.6 percent at present,
Soldatenko said.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the number of people aged between 15 and 49 will
decrease by 2.5 million, while residents above 60 will make up 30
percent of the population, much higher than the 21.2 percent for
the time being.
</P>
<P>
He suggested the government raise the age of retirement.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
