<HEADLINE> Panama, U.S. to Establish Anti-drug Center </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANAMA CITY, July 17 (Xinhua) -- Panamanian Foreign Minister
Ricardo Alberto Arias said today that his country and the United
States are negotiating on setting up an anti-drug center in the
U.S. Howard Air Base on the banks of the Panama Canal.
</P>
<P>
Arias said that the two governments agreed Tuesday to start
formal negotiations to establish a multilateral center against
drug trafficking in Panama.
</P>
<P>
The two governments had negotiated the matter in an informal
way, but no concrete results were obtained, he said.
</P>
<P>
The Panamanian government set up a negotiating commission
conisting of Jorge Ritter, Minister of State for Canal Affairs,
Adolfo Ahumada, Foreign Ministry counselor, and lawyer Eloy
Alfaro.
</P>
<P>
The negotiations will be bilateral in principle, Ritter
said. Other countries which are interested in participating in the
center can join the negotiations later.
</P>
<P>
The establishment of the center was proposed by Panamanian
President Ernesto Perez Balladares during a meeting of the Group
of Rio in September 1995, said Arias.
</P>
<P>
"It is convenient to establish the center taking advantage of
the Howard Air Base installations," he said. The base is located
on the banks of the Panama Canal, which will revert to Panama in
1999. 
</P>
