<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NATO Expansion Creates New Problems, Russian PM Says </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 17 (Xinhua) -- NATO's eastward expansion has not
solved existing problems, but created new ones, Russian Prime
Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin said here today.
</P>
<P>
The military bloc's expansion into Eastern Europe has turned
the plan to change its military and political structures and its
strategic conception into something in the distant future,
Chernomyrdin told the Interfax news agency before leaving for
Brussels.
</P>
<P>
Russian Foreign Minister Yevgeny Primakov said Wednesday that
Russia remains opposed to NATO's eastward expansion and this
position will not change.
</P>
<P>
At a summit in Madrid earlier this month, NATO invited Poland,
Hungary and the Czech Republic to join the military alliance.
</P>
<P>
Knowing that the three countries would join the alliance at its
Madrid summit, President Boris Yeltsin decided not to attend the
meeting, Chernomyrdin said.
</P>
<P>
He said Russia does not doubt the necessity of building an
equal partnership of cooperation with NATO.
</P>
<P>
NATO's expansion has become an objective reality, and Russia
has to make efforts to adapt itself to the reality, he said.
</P>
<P>
The signing of a Founding Act on May 27, which establishes a
new post-Cold War Russia-NATO relationship, reduces to the minimum
the unfavorable military consequences from the expansion upon
Russia, he said.
</P>
<P>
On Russia-Japan relations, he said Russia is seeking to sign a
peace treaty with Japan on the basis that neither country's
national dignity is damaged.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the inaugural meeting of the NATO-Russia partnership
council, established following the signing of the Founding Act,
has been postponed after a wrangle over the chairmanship, reports
said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The council was to have met in Brussels Thursday, but NATO and
Russia have been unable to agree on the mechanics of how a
rotating presidency involving both sides would work in practice,
the reports said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
