<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Flood Situation Improves Further in Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, July 18 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh's overall flood situation
improved further as most of the rivers in the Brahmaputra, the
Meghna and South Eastern hill basins registered fall and water
began to recede slowly from flood-hit areas.
</P>
<P>
According to Flood Information Center, only four rivers were
flowing above their respective danger levels at several points up
till today.
</P>
<P>
During the period of monsoon rain-fed floods beginning from
July 9, more than 3.5 million people in 22 districts were affected
by the devastating floods that caused extensive damage to crops
and property.
</P>
<P>
The death toll from flood-related incidents rose to 77
according to official counts.
</P>
<P>
The figures were given at a high-level inter-ministerial
meeting held on Thursday. The meeting reviewed the overall flood
situation, relief activities and rehabilitation programs
undertaken by different ministries and departments.
</P>
<P>
It was informed that standing crops on 0.1 million acres were
completely damaged and around 3,000 cattle perished in the flood
onslaughts.
</P>
<P>
The flood destroyed more than 600 kilometers of roads while
partially damaging 2,500 kilometers of roads in the affected
districts.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was informed that diarrhea broke out in the
affected areas following the recession of flood waters. Seven
people have so far died of diarrhea.
</P>
<P>
To meet with the water borne disease, the government had made
an emergency arrangement to set up 50 deep tubewells in the
flood-hit areas of southern Bandarban district. Similar
arrangement has also been made for other flood-hit areas of the
country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
