<DOCNO> XIE19970718.0162 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Telecom Industry Stays on Fast Track </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 18 (Xinhua) -- China's post and telecom industry
registered a year-on-year growth of 32.9 percent in business
turnover in the first half of this year, according to the
Ministry of Posts and Telecommunications.
</P>
<P>
Statistics released by the ministry show that the post and
telecom services scored a turnover of 80.9 billion yuan during
that period, up 32.9 percent, and much higher than the country's
average industrial growth of 13.8 percent in the period.
</P>
<P>
The earnings of post and telecom services totaled 79.8 billion
yuan, meeting 51 percent of the annual target.
</P>
<P>
In terms of post services, postal savings and stamp collection
recorded noticeable growth. The income from postal services
reached 12.8 billion yuan, a rise of more than 50 percent owing to
the adjustment of postal fees.
</P>
<P>
Telecom business witnessed steady growth; business turnover in
the first half hit 73.8 billion yuan, up 35.5 percent, while the
income in the period reached 67 billion yuan, up 34.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
Local telecom officials said that of the telecom income mix,
the proportion of long-distance and local calls accounted for 36.4
percent and 30.6 percent, respectively. Income from mobile phone
services made up 33.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
The number of new telephone users in the first six months
reached 10.94 million in the first half of this year. Telecom
experts predicted that the total number of users may exceed Japan's
this year, ranking second in the world, after the United States.
</P>
<P>
In the first 181 days, the number of mobile phone users in
China hit 9.74 million, a net increase of 2.89 million.
</P>
<P>
Progress was also made in the infrastructure construction. The
country in the first six months added 5.68 million lines to the
capacity of program controlled switchboards, bringing the total
number of lines to 98.51 million. It is predicted that the
benchmark of 100 million lines will be reached in the third
quarter.
</P>
<P>
Post and telecom authorities completed a total investment of
28.5 billion yuan in fixed assets during that period, up 32.9
percent.
</P>
<P>
In data communications, China now has 140,000 terminals with
70,000 subscribers for ChinaPAC (China Packaging Exchanges);
190,000 terminals with around 80,000 users for ChinaDDN (China
Digital Data Network); and 80,000 users for ChinaNet hooked up
with Internet. 
</P>
</TEXT>
