<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German, Austrian, Italian Leaders Agree to Lift Borders </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
VIENNA, July 17 (Xinhua) -- German Chancellor Helmut Kohl,
Austrian Chancellor Viktor Klima and Italian Prime Minister Romano
Prodi agreed today that their joint border controls will be
removed on April 1 next year.
</P>
<P>
The three leaders, met in the western Austrian town of
Innsbruck today, agreed that the Schengen accords, which allow
free movement across borders for signatory countries, will take
effect in Austria on December 1 and come into force in Italy on
October 26.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, the borders of Austria and Italy will be
totally free to the Schengen signatory countries on April 1, 1998.
</P>
<P>
The two countries will also share common visa policy, Schengen
information network and police cooperation.
</P>
<P>
On March 26, 1995, Belgium, the Netherlands, Luxembourg,
Germany, France, Spain and Portugal began to implement the
Schengen accords, which were signed on June 14, 1990.
</P>
<P>
Although Austria signed the Schengen accords in April, 1995,
the European Union has postponed its entry into the accords,
fearing that Austria's border with eastern European countries will
not be properly patrolled. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970718.0164 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan Provides 1.88 Billion Dollar Aid to Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 18 (Xinhua) -- Japan increased its official
development assistance (ODA) to Indonesia this year by 3.5
percent, reaching 213.748 billion yen, according to the Japanese
embassy in Indonesia today.
</P>
<P>
However, the Japanese embassy said in a press release that the
ODA this year is slightly smaller than last year's if converted
into the U.S. dollar which amounted to 1.88 U.S. billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Last year, Japan's ODA to Indonesia was 1.91 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Japan announced its ODA to Indonesia at the sixth meeting of
the Consultative Group for Indonesia (CGI) held in Tokyo on July
16 and 17.
</P>
<P>
In spite of the fact that the Japanese government's ODA budget
for the 1997-98 fiscal year will be cut by 10 percent over 1996-97
due to the recent austere financial condition, Japan has increased
its commitment of ODA to Indonesia by 7.15 billion yen over
1996-97, which is a 3.5 percent increase in terms of yen, he
added.
</P>
<P>
At the Tokyo meeting, CGI members decided to provide 5.3
billion dollars of soft loans to Indonesia. Last year, CGI
committed 5.26 billion dollars in new loan and grants.
</P>
<P>
The CGI groups the U.S., Australia, Austria, Belgium, Denmark,
Finland, Britain, Italy, Japan, Germany, Canada, South Korea,
Norway, France, New Zealand, Spain, Switzerland, Sweden and some
international monetary organizations including the World Bank.
</P>
</TEXT>
