accused Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu of lacking
sincerity and wanting to destroy the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the Austrian daily newspaper Die Presse
published today, Arafat said, "Netanyahu does not want peace; on
the contrary he is destroying the peace process."
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian leader, who visited Austria Tuesday and
Wednesday, also condemned Israel's recent arrest of Palestinian
policemen, saying such an act violated the autonomy accord.
</P>
<P>
But Arafat added that most Israelis are supporting the peace
process.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian-Israeli peace talks have been stalled since the
Jewish state began construction in March of a housing settlement
for around 30,000 people in east Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
During his visit to Austria, Arafat met with Austrian
Chancellor Viktor Klima, National Council President Heinz Fischer
and Foreign Minister Wolfgang Schuessel.
</P>
<P>
The Austrian leaders said they support the peace process
and the U.N. resolution condemning Israel's settlement policies in
the Palestinian territories.
</P>
<P>
Arafat hoped the European Union and Austria would pressure on
Israel and revive the deadlocked Middle East peace process.
</P>
