<DOCNO> XIE19970718.0170 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> CCF Plans to Help More Handicapped Orphans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 18 (Xinhua) -- Dang Kang no longer fears
answering his teachers' questions during classroom
instructions. He now smiles.
</P>
<P>
The 10-year-old boy was abandoned by his parents because he was
born with a cleft palate. The couple who adopted him were too poor
to afford the expensive surgery -- until the China Charity
Federation (CCF) stepped in.
</P>
<P>
Dang is one of 1,849 children who have regained their smiles
after having face-lift operations funded by CCF. About 1,200 more
cleft palate-afflicted orphans are on the organization's plan for
this year, according to today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
"If chance permits, we hope to extend the project from orphans
to afflicted children in poor families," said Cui Naifu, president
of the federation.
</P>
<P>
The federation, a free bridge joining loving hearts and the
needy, is trying to include more people in their programs.
</P>
<P>
It plans to support 10,000 families in China's drought-stricken
northwestern area by helping dig water cellars this year, the
paper said.
</P>
<P>
Each cellar will cost 800 yuan (96.40 US dollars). The expense
may be paid by one donor or shared by two, and donors' names will
be engraved on the cellar, Cui said.
</P>
<P>
In Beijing's rural area, 2,500 poor students have recently been
paired with people who will finance their schooling.
</P>
<P>
Established in 1994, the CCF is the first national charity
organization and the biggest nongovernmental, non-profit
institution in China, with 19 provincial branches and 49 groups in
its membership. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
