<HEADLINE> Death Toll in Indonesia's Plane Crash Rises to 26 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 18 (Xinhua) -- The death toll from Thursday's
crash of an Indonesian plane in West Java rose to 26 today, Antara
news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
A fokker-27 plane of Sempati Airline crashed ten minutes after
takeoff from Bandung, West Java, at 11:45 a.m., killing at least
26 people including five crew, and injuring 26 others.
</P>
<P>
The plane, which was going to Jakarta, capital of Indonesia,
crashed near a housing complex just after takeoff from the Husein
Sastranegara Airport in Bandung.
</P>
<P>
Transportation Minister Haryanto Dhanutirto, who arrived on the
scene 15 minutes after the incident, said the pilot, F.X. Banbang,
reported engine trouble to the control tower before the plane went
down.
</P>
<P>
"Perhaps the pilot attempted to make an emergency landing at
Sulaeman airport," Dhanutirto said. Sulaeman airport is located
just 200 meters from the crash site.
</P>
<P>
The fokker-27 is a twin-turboprop plane that can carry up to 52
passengers.
</P>
<P>
The accident was the third domestic plane crash in three
months.
</P>
<P>
A plane belonging to the Merpati Airline crashed in April near
Belitung, South Sumatra, killing 15 people and injuring 31 others.
</P>
<P>
In early July, a CN-212 belonging to Merpati Airline crashed
near Ambon, Maluku, killing three crew on board.  
</P>
</TEXT>
