<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Peru to Enforce Fishing Closed Season </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LIMA, July 17 (Xinhua) -- A closed season on the capture of
anchovy will be in force starting Friday along its shores,
Peruvian Fishing Ministry announced.
</P>
<P>
The Fishing Ministry said the decision was adopted in
accordance with the recommendation of the Peruvian Institute of
the Sea, which said that the effects of the El Nino have disrupted
the distribution and concentration patterns of the anchovy.
</P>
<P>
El Nino is a warm inshore current annually flowing south along
the coast of Ecuador and about every seven to ten years, extending
down the coast of Peru, where it has devastating effect on fish,
weather and crops.
</P>
<P>
"This puts the stocks in very unstable conditions to sustain
the next fishing seasons, taking into account also that the
established capture quotas have been fulfilled," added the
ministry.
</P>
<P>
Peruvian Sea Institute research has shown that the El Nino
phenomenon has affected negatively the fishing resources,
especially anchovy, which has caused a lack of renewal of the
adult stock, which diminished the rate of reproduction. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970718.0173 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Medicare Overpayments Accounted for 14 percent Last Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 17 (Xinhua) -- Medicare, the federal health
insurance program in the United States, improperly paid 23 billion
dollars last year, government auditors said.
</P>
<P>
That means 14 cents of every dollar spent by the government's
largest health care program was lost to fraud, abuse or simple
errors.
</P>
<P>
Members of a House subcommittee said the audit underscored the
need for the Health and Human Services Department (HHS) to
exercise much stronger controls to root out payment problems.
</P>
<P>
HHS Inspector General June Gibbs Brow, whose office conducted
the audit, said an estimated 23.2 billion, or 14 percent, of the
168.6 billion dollars Medicare paid in 1996 to health care
providers including hospitals, doctors and labs was improper.
</P>
<P>
The audit report was released Thursday at a meeting of House
Ways and Means health subcommittee. Lawmakers recently drafted a
balanced-budget plan to reduce spending on Medicare by 115 billion
dollars over the next five years because the health program for
the elderly and disabled is in danger of bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
Since it was created three decades ago, Medicare has grown to
serve more than 38 million people who generate 800 million medical
bills a year.
</P>
<P>
The most persistent problem found was bills submitted by health
care providers to the government with insufficient or no
documentation of the care provided -- accounting for nearly half
of all improper payments.
</P>
<P>
Other irregularities include bills for medically unnecessary
treatment, for treatment that Medicare does not cover, and bills
for expensive services when cheaper treatment was actually
provided.
</P>
<P>
Brown said the audit did not distinguish whether errors were
honest mistakes or attempted fraud but she said providers were
getting more aggressive in their efforts to maximize profits.
</P>
<P>
Advocates for the nation's hospitals maintain Medicare's
complicated, bureaucratic billing system is to blame.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970718.0174 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bulgaria Extends Debt Payment to Poland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Sofia, July 17 (Xinhua) -- The Bulgarian government extended
the July 31 deadline for the settlement of the Bulgarian debt to
Poland worth some 100 million transferable roubles by the year's
end, Minister of Trade and Tourism Valentin Vassilev told the
government's press office.
</P>
<P>
Bulgaria is repaying its debt in farm and tobacco products.
</P>
<P>
Poland and Hungary insist that Bulgaria must repay its debts
towards them prior to the signing of an agreement on the
establishment of free trade areas with them. The signing of this
agreement is related to Bulgaria's admission as a full member of
the Central European Free Trade Agreement.
</P>
<P>
In a joint report delivered Thursday Minister of Trade and
Tourism Valentin Vassilev and Finance Minister Mouravei Radev
propose that this country's debts towards Poland and Hungary worth
195.3 million transferable roubles are further settled in goods
and services. The report was moved to the Council of Ministers,
the Trade Ministry press office said.
</P>
<P>
Under protocols signed in 1991, Bulgaria is committed to
settle trade deficits, accumulated in the period of rouble
payments, in goods and services according to 1990 prices. The
debts should have been settled by the end of 1991 and the
remaining amount paid in convertible currency. However the
condition for the recalculation of the outstanding amounts in
hard currency is unfavourable for Bulgaria and the country has not
yet accepted it, the two ministers' joint report says. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970718.0175 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Urges Americans to Confront Racial Problems </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 17 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton on
Thursday called on Americans to confront "often painful issues" of
race so that they won't destroy the country's future.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to the National Association of Black Journalists in
Chicago, the president said he is "a little stumped" by the
"shocking" consequences of plunging minority graduate school
enrollments in California and Texas, where affirmative action
programs were ended.
</P>
<P>
A formal effort to redress past discrimination, Affirmative
action aims at ensuring blacks and other historically
disadvantaged groups equal access to employment, educational, and
business opportunities.
</P>
<P>
"I don't understand that," news reports quoted Clinton as
saying. "It's a great concern to me. I think it is moving the
country in exactly the wrong direction."
</P>
<P>
He said the fact that significantly fewer minorities will
attend law schools in those two states next year shows what can
happen when Americans fail to talk out and resolve racial
problems.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said, "We really have not only an opportunity but an
obligation to address and to better resolve the vexing,
perplexing, often painful issues surrounding our racial history
and our future."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
