<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Brazil Adopts Oil Industry Privatization Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO, July 17 (Xinhua) -- The Brazilian Senate
approved on Wednesday night a law permitting private investment in
oil industry.
</P>
<P>
According to the new law, a National Oil Agency (ANP) will be
set up which will be in charge of regulating, contracting, and
overseeing the business of the sector.
</P>
<P>
As soon as the new law is signed by President Fernando Henrique
Cardoso, the state enterprise Petroleos de Brazil (Petrobras) will
be authorized to negotiate with domestic or foreign enterprises,
to sell assets such as refineries, oil wells, pipelines, ships,
and subsidiaries.
</P>
<P>
Petrobras must present ANP in a three-month period, according
to the law, a program of exploration, development, and production
that will locate its operations zones for future concessions to
the private sector.
</P>
<P>
Eleven of the 74 senators present during the plenary session
voted against the project Wednesday night. 
</P>
</TEXT>
