<HEADLINE> Russia Calls for Cooperation with EU in Fighting Crime </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 17 (Xinhua) -- Russian Prime Minister Viktor
Chernomyrdin Thursday stressed the need for his country to
cooperate more closely with the European Union in fighting
organized crime.
</P>
<P>
EU member states should sign cooperation agreements with
Russia, and interior and judicial departments of the two sides
should increase their contact, Chernomyrdin told the Interfax news
agency.
</P>
<P>
Russia and EU members should make concerted efforts to combat
organized crime, and Russia's law-enforcement authorities and
secret service departments are ready to further cooperate with the
EU in fighting organized crime, smuggling, illegal weapons
shipment and drugs, he said.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister noted that Russia's criminal law has come
into effect this year, and "more important laws" are to be passed,
including documents on fighting organized crime.
</P>
<P>
The country has adopted a series of measures on fighting crime,
and some 55,000 criminals have been convicted over the past four
years, he said.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the increase in economic and bribery crimes
have seriously affected the nation's image, trade and investment
environment.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, the crime rate in Russia is lower than that in
the United States and Germany, he added. In Russia, the annual
rate is 1,800 cases per 100,000 people, while in the U.S., the
rate stands at 15,000 cases, and in Germany, 8,300 cases. 
</P>
</TEXT>
