<HEADLINE> U.S. Sends Solarz to Asia on Cambodia Mission </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 17 (Xinhua) -- The United States is sending
former congressman Stephen Solarz to Asia as a special envoy on a
mission for a resolution to the recent Cambodia crisis, the State
Department said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Solarz will visit China, Japan, Thailand, Indonesia, Malaysia
and Cambodia, State Department spokesman Nicholas Burns told
reporters.
</P>
<P>
During his visit, Solarz will discuss with leaders of these
countries "how best to uphold and restore the principles of the
1991 Paris peace accords so that all Cambodian parties can
operate freely and free and fair elections can take place in
1998," Burns said.
</P>
<P>
He was at the request of Secretary of State Madeleine Albright
"to explore possible resolution of the crisis in Cambodia," Burns
continued.
</P>
<P>
The Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) will hold a
meeting later this month and Cambodia will be high on the agenda
when the gathering is under way.
</P>
<P>
Albright "felt strongly that we had to have a series of
diplomatic conversations with ASEAN countries as well as Hun Sen
to ... make sure we had best possible framework" going into
ASEAN, Burns said.
</P>
<P>
Burns described Solarz's appointment as a "one trip" mission,
not a permanent appointment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
