<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain Announces Dates for Polls in Scotland, Wales </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 17 (Xinhua) -- The British government today
announced dates of referendums in Scotland and Wales on plans to
give the two nations their own parliaments.
</P>
<P>
Scottish Secretary Donald Dewar said the plebiscite in Scotland
will take place on September 11 and a similar poll on the setting
up of a Welsh senate will be held a week later.
</P>
<P>
The plans for so-called "devolution" were a key issue in
Britain's May 1 election, with the Conservatives warning that the
government's plans were the first step on a slippery slope towards
the break-up of Britain.
</P>
<P>
In the referendum, Scottish voters will be asked to endorse the
government's plans for the new parliament to control most of
Scotland's internal affairs.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Home Secretary Jack Straw announced that legislation
will be introduced soon to allow all Britain's 87 members of the
European Parliament to be chosen by a proportional representation
(PR) system for the first time in 1999.
</P>
<P>
Britain is at present the odd member state out in the European
Union in electing most of its MEPs by a first-past-the-post
system, although the three Northern Irish members have always been
elected by PR.
</P>
<P>
First-past-the-post gives larger parties a big advantage, and
helped the ruling Labor Party to win 62 seats at the last European
parliament elections in 1994. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970718.0203 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Publishes Report on Youth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, July 17 (Xinhua) -- Young people in the European
Union (EU) countries are staying longer in education, taking
longer to cross from training to work, and waiting longer before
starting families, it was learned here today.
</P>
<P>
Age at which at least 50 percent of young people have a job or
are seeking one rose from 18 in 1987 to 20 in 1995, according to a
report by Eurostat, the EU's statistical office.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 60 percent of the 18-year-olds in the EU countries were
in education or training. Belgium had the highest rate of 88
percent while the lowest rate of the kind -- 38 percent -- was
registered in the UK.
</P>
<P>
Across the EU, 17 percent of the 18-year-olds combined training
with work, usually part-time, says the report.
</P>
<P>
In 1995, the issue of unemployment became a big worry for the
EU's young people. Between 1991 and 1995, the jobless rate of
young people under the age of 25 rose in all EU member states
except Denmark and Ireland.
</P>
<P>
The report says that when young people were asked about the
main difficulties they faced, 70 percent of them put unemployment
at the top of the list. Next came inadequate education or
training.
</P>
<P>
Between 1960 and 1980, young people tended to leave their
parents' homes early, the report says. But this trend changed in
the following decade, particularly for those aged 25 to 29 in
southern member states.
</P>
<P>
Living together outside marriage is very common in Denmark,
France and the UK but is rare in Ireland and southern member
states such as Portugal and Italy.
</P>
<P>
There are around 50 million people aged 15 to 24 in the EU
countries, who account for 14 percent of the whole population.
This rises to 80 million if people aged 25 to 29 are included.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970718.0204 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-18 </DATE_TIME>
