<HEADLINE> U.S. Dollar Rises Against yen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, July 17 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. dollar rose against the
Japanese yen in New York Thursday after Japan said its trade
surplus did not widen in June as much as traders had feared.
</P>
<P>
The dollar also ended higher against the German mark and Swiss
franc.
</P>
<P>
In late afternoon trading in New York, the dollar cost 116.07
yen, up from 115.52 yen Wednesday. It cost 1.7941 marks, up from
1.7906, and 1.4828 Swiss francs, up from 1.4760. The pound
weakened to 1.6722 U.S. dollars from 1.6784 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The dollar rose on the news that Japan's unadjusted trade
surplus grew to 934.21 billion yen in June. That was up 27.7
percent from a year earlier but well below economists'
expectations.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, the dollar hit a six-year high against the mark,
topping 1.8000 marks, amid strong optimism in New York about the
health of the U.S. economy, the strong U.S. stock market and doubts
about Europe's single currency.
</P>
<P>
Nonetheless, the dollar has encountered resistance when it
surpasses the 1.8000 mark level.
</P>
<P>
Other dollar rates in New York, compared with Wednesday: 6.0550
French Francs, up from 6.0435; 2,744.50 Italian lire, up from
1,738.00; and 1.3773 Canadian dollars, up from 1.3737.  
</P>
</TEXT>
