<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-17 16:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus Pleased with EU Accession, Peace March </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, July 17 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus said today that it is
pleased with the progress in its accession to the European Union
(EU) and the efforts to end the country's ethnic conflicts.
</P>
<P>
Government spokesman Manolis Christofides made the remark at
his daily press briefing here today, adding "a lot of caution is
needed by all in order to cover the distance toward these two
goals."
</P>
<P>
This was against the backdrop that the European Commission
confirmed Tuesday that EU accession talks with Cyprus and other
five Eastern European states will start next year, and leaders of
the Greek and Turkish Cypriot sides opened direct negotiations
near New York under the U.N. sponsorship.
</P>
<P>
President Glafcos Clerides and the Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf
Denktash decided at the face-to-face talks that they will hold
second round of talks in Geneva between August 11 and 16.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that by December all details regarding
accession talks with the EU will be known, as the
Inter-governmental Conference (IGC) will formally end in October.
</P>
<P>
The EU decided in March 1995 that accession negotiations will
begin with Cyprus six months after the end of the IGC.
</P>
<P>
Christofides reiterated that a solution to the Cyprus problem
will help Cyprus' bid to join the EU, but stressed that even if
there is no solution reached at that time accession talks will
begin.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman also urged Turkey to change its attitude for the
sake of its own European course.
</P>
<P>
Turkey, which was reportedly excluded from the EU accession
talks, has threatened to annex the northern part of the island if
Cyprus joins the EU.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been partitioned since 1974 when Turkish troops
took over the northern third of the island following a failed
coup by Greek Cypriots allied with the military junta that ruled
Greece at the time. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
