<HEADLINE> UNITA Members Urged to Respect UN Observers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, July 17 (xinhua) -- Angola's former rebel movement
UNITA today appealed to all its members and supporters to respect
the United Nations observers and officials from humanitarian
organizations, the Angola News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
In a communique issued in its headquarters in Angola's central
city Bailundo, the Political Committee of the National Union for
the Total Independence of Angola (UNITA) expressed its regret
over the incident that a helicopter of the United Nations
Observers Mission was detained on July 11 in Angola's northeastern areas
under UNITA control.
</P>
<P>
The communique said that the incident has damaged the image of
the UNITA and pledged that such an incident will not happen any
longer.
</P>
<P>
The UNITA urged all its members, supporters and residents
under its control to strictly respect the UN observers, members
of non-government organizations and their properties. Any
offender will be punished, added the communique.
</P>
<P>
Recently, the UNITA soldiers have twice detained UN aircraft
and their crew members, and also have abused the UN and NGO
staffs and confiscated their properties. On monday, the UN
Observers Mission issued a statement, condemning the acts of
UNITA soldiers and requesting the UNITA to take measures to
prevent such acts from happening again. 
</P>
