<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Nominates Shelton to Be Top US Military Officer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 17 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
today nominated four-star Army Gen. Henry Shelton to be the next
chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, the president's top
military adviser.
</P>
<P>
"He has distinguished himself as a decorated soldier," Clinton
said at a White House Rose Garden ceremony attended also by the
current Joint Chiefs chairman, Army Gen. John Shalikashvili, who
is scheduled to retire at the end of September.
</P>
<P>
"From Vietnam to Desert Storm he has proven his skill and
courage in combat," Clinton said, adding that Shelton was a
"thinker" with a "unique perspective" on security challenges
expected to face America in the coming years.
</P>
<P>
Shelton, 55, a 34-year veteran who commanded the U.S. military
operation in Haiti three years ago, now heads the Special
Operations Command, an elite group of 47,000 Army Navy and Air
Force troops which was created in 1987 under legislation sponsored
by then-Sen. William Cohen of Maine, now the defense secretary.
</P>
<P>
If confirmed by the Senate, Shelton would be the third
consecutive Army general to serve as chairman, behind
Shalikashvili and Gen. Colin Powell.
</P>
<P>
Shelton is considered a decisive and combat-tested leader, a
commander of helicopter forces in the Persian Gulf War and in the
Army's Green Berets in Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
Like Powell and Shalikashvili, Shelton is not a graduate of
West Point, the Army's military academy. He graduated from North
Carolina State University. He was born in Tarboro, North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
In a recent article on his command published by the Pentagon,
Shelton said the United States must prepare itself for a new era
in which terrorism, ethnic conflict and even the threats of
chemical, biological and cyberspace warfare could arise.
</P>
<P>
Shelton noted his troops "are not designed to win wars
single-handedly, but they can help prevent and deter them." For
the next decade, the nation can expect that "operations short of
war" will dominate its security concerns, he added.
</P>
<P>
Shelton was chosen as the candidate for the chairman after the
candidacy of Air Force Gen. Joseph Ralston was scuttled by his
disclosure of an adulterous affair. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
