<HEADLINE> Southern African Bio-medical Research Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 17 (Xinhua) -- The two-day Bio-medical Research
and Training Institute (BRTI) meeting ended here today with a
call for the Southern African Development Community (SADC)
states to cooperate in improving the quality of health in the region.
</P>
<P>
Namibia's Permanent Secretary of Health and Social Services
Kalemba Shangula told the closing session that SADC governments
should provide adequate funds for the setting up of a regional
research and training health center.
</P>
<P>
"What is clear in the region is that, given the present
research environment of limited financial and human resources,
organizations like BRTI can play a major role in harnessing the
potential that we have within the SADC community," said Shangula.
</P>
<P>
Professor Wen Kalima of Tanzania said organizations such as
BRTI should help African scientists by lobbying their respective
governments for better pay to plug the brain drain.
</P>
<P>
He said it was essential that governments in the region should
support research relevant both to the region and globally.
</P>
<P>
BRTI, which aims to collaborate with institutes and
laboratories of the SADC, is a regional research and training
institute formed two years ago to spearhead a common approach to
the region's health problems. 
</P>
</TEXT>
