<HEADLINE> Bonn Strongly Against EU-Proposed Farm Subsidy Cut </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, July 17 (Xinhua) -- The German government today expressed
firm opposition to European Union (EU) proposals to reduce farm
subsidies which currently account for about half of the EU's 86
billion ECU (78 billion US dollar) annual budget.
</P>
<P>
German Agriculture Minister Jochen Borchert described the
radical proposals as "superfluous," "contradictory" and comprising
"a grave change which disadvantages the German farmer and
taxpayer."
</P>
<P>
He noted that neither the planned EU eastward expansion nor
negotiations with the World Trade Organization could justify the
proposals, which were put forward by EU commission president
Jacques Santer and EU farm commissioner Franz Fischler.
</P>
<P>
Under the proposals, a one-third cut would come as a result in
prices EU guaranteed to its farmers, and the farmers would be
compensated through increased direct aid payments.
</P>
<P>
The EU guaranteed prices are above those in the global markets.
Bochert said that he was particularly opposed to reducing the
guaranteed prices for beef, grain and milk.
</P>
<P>
There are currently fears in the EU of a soaring farm subsidy
bill and more excess of farm products priced out of global markets
as a result of the rising EU agricultural production and the
future entry into the EU of such big farming nations as Poland.
</P>
<P>
Borchert said that he saw no need at present for a major reform
of the Common Agricultural Policy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
