<HEADLINE> Kenya's Ruling Party Softens Tune on Reforms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 17 (Xinhua) -- Kenya's ruling party Kenya
African National Union (KANU) today recommended the government
propose a bill in parliament for enactment of a commission to
review the constitution and make proposals.
</P>
<P>
Kenyan Vice-President George Saitoti, who is also KANU's
Vice-President, said that the ruling party suggested the
government issue a Statute Law bill in the current session of the
parliament to allow the repeal or amendment of laws charged as
oppressive.
</P>
<P>
The laws charged as oppressive include the Public Order Act on
public rallies, the Preservation of Public Security Act which
allows detention without trial, as well as other nine laws, said
Saitoti at a press conference.
</P>
<P>
"They (opposition parties) asked for so-called minimum
constitutional reforms. We have not only agreed to these, but
have also proposed that comprehensive reforms be examined,"
Nicholas Biwott, a powerful minister of state, told reporters.
</P>
<P>
The KANU National Executive Council (NEC) has "reaffirmed the
commitment that there should be free and fair elections in a
peaceful atmosphere," said Saitoti.
</P>
<P>
Saitoti's statement is seen as one of remarkable signals that
the government is softening its stance on the constitutional
reforms demanded by opposition parties soon after nationwide
violent confrontation between the two sides claimed 14 lives on
July 7.
</P>
<P>
Kenyan President Daniel arap Moi met with opposition leader in
parliament Kijana Wamalwa on Wednesday and 17 key Christian and
Moslem religious leaders on Tuesday over the constitutional
reforms.
</P>
<P>
The two sides agreed that time and mechanism for affecting
constitutional reforms would be discussed in subsequent meetings,
one of them expected to be held next week.
</P>
<P>
Moi also announced on Wednesday that the public rallies
licences will be automatically granted on application, regarded
as a key concession to the reform demands.
</P>
<P>
From May to July, violence has been escalating when the
opposition repeatedly tried to hold rallies without governmental
permits in a bid to press for constitutional reforms before the
general elections. All the rallies were broken up by the police.
</P>
<P>
Under the current constitution, any candidate, if he wins no
less than 25 percent of votes respectively in five of the eight
provinces of Kenya, he can be qualified as a legal president.
</P>
<P>
Now the opposition leaders urged to change the clause,
demanding the future president get more than 50 percent of the
total votes nationwide, otherwise form a coalition government
with other parties. But this has been refused by Moi. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
