<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 3.7 Mln Active Businesses in UK at Start of 1996 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 17 (Xinhua) -- There were an estimated 3.7 million
active businesses in Britain at the start of 1996, according to
new statistics published today.
</P>
<P>
It is an increase of over 18,000 enterprises since the start of
1995, showed the Small and Medium Enterprise (SME) statistics for
the UK, 1996.
</P>
<P>
The Statistical Bulletin contained a size breakdown of the
number of businesses in the UK, from small traders with no
employees to those with 500 or more employees.
</P>
<P>
It also showed the contribution to employment and turnover made
by businesses of different sizes, industry by industry.
</P>
<P>
Of the 3.7 million businesses in 1996, over 2.5 million were
"size class zero" business -- those made up of sole traders or
partners without employees.
</P>
<P>
The majority of the 1.2 million businesses with employees were
small (fewer than 50 employees). Only 26,000 were medium sized (50
to 249 employees) and almost 7,000 were large (250 or more
employees).
</P>
<P>
Small businesses, including those without employees, accounted
for over 99 percent of businesses, 46 percent of non-government
employment and (excluding the finance sector) 38 percent of
turnover.
</P>
<P>
In contrast, the 7,000 largest business accounted for 42
percent of non-government employment and 44 percent of turnover.
</P>
<P>
At the start of 1996, at least 99 percent of businesses in all
but one industry sector were SMEs. In the exception, the
electricity, gas and water supply sector, only 85.7 percent of
businesses were SMEs, a decline from 90 percent in 1995.
</P>
<P>
The share of employment in small businesses was higher than
average in agriculture, forestry and fishing and in most service
industries at the start of 1996. Small businesses continued to
dominate employment in the construction industry.
</P>
<P>
Some industries were still relatively dominated by medium and
large sized businesses; they are electricity, gas and water
supply, mining and quarrying, manufacturing and financial
intermediation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
