<HEADLINE> Use of More Speed Cameras Urged in UK to Reduce </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 17 (Xinhua) -- More government funding is called
for in Britain for increasing the use of speed cameras as a trial
shows that speed cameras have led to a 70 percent reduction in
fatal road accidents, said local press reports today.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that a trial in four west London boroughs,
which monitored the effectiveness of speed cameras, has led to a
60 million pound (100 million US dollar) saving in accident costs.
</P>
<P>
The Parliamentary Advisory Council for Transport Safety said,
"Conclusion from this trial are clear: speed cameras save lives,
not just of car occupants but also of vulnerable road users."
</P>
<P>
"This is yet another reason why the government must look again
at the funding of cameras," it added.
</P>
<P>
Figures show that the cameras have led to a 28 percent
reduction in serious accidents and an 8 percent decrease in minor
accidents.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 3,600 people were killed in Britain in road accidents
last year and a third was due to speeding, according to official
figures. 
</P>
</TEXT>
