<DOCNO> XIE19970718.0232 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-17 19:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 17 (Xinhua) -- The following are business briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- A visiting World Bank official said here today that
the bank is to offer 15 million U.S. dollars to Jordan to help
improve the kingdom's health sector, Radio Jordan reported.
</P>
<P>
The grant will be used to restructure the health sector,
improve its efficiency and upgrade the health and pharmaceutical
services in cooperation with the private sector, said Goerge
Sheeper, who was responsible for the health affairs of the World
Bank.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank has so far lent 1.4 billion dollars to Jordan
since the early 1960s and all but 250 million dollars had been
disbursed by the end of last year.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Eight countries signed today a protocol on
cooperation in railway transportation, the semi-official Anatolia
News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The protocol, signed by Turkey, Iran, Pakistan, Kazakhstan,
Azerbaijan, Uzbekistan, Tajikistan and Turkmenistan in Istanbul,
the largest city of Turkey, is aimed at improving cooperation
among the concerned countries in railway transportation.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the signing ceremony, Director General of Turkish
Railways (TCDD) Tekin Cinar emphasized the importance of the
Iran-Turkmenistan railway which makes the railway transportation
between Turkey and the Central Asian countries possible.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- Gulf Air has sharply cut its debts to 923 million
dollars by the end of June from 1.566 billion dollars in December
1995, a statement issued by the regional carrier said today.
</P>
<P>
A further reduction is anticipated before the end of 1997, the
statement said.
</P>
<P>
The debts of the Bahrain-based airline jointly owned by the
governments of Bahrain, Oman, Qatar and Abu Dhabi Emirate of the
United Arab Emirates (UAE) resulted from a flurry of buying new
aircraft in the late 1980s and opening uneconomic routes.
</P>
<P>
The debt-ridden carrier has cut jobs, sold aircraft and closed
unprofitable routes to cut losses.
</P>
<P>
At the end of 1996, the airline has sold six Boeing 767
aircraft and closed routes to and from New York, Geneva and
Johannesburg.
</P>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY -- Kuwait is about to authorize the marketing in
Kuwait of three investment funds established outside Kuwait by
Kuwaitis and foreign companies.
</P>
<P>
Shamlan Al-Hassawi, Kuwaiti Chairwoman of the stock exchange
and investment portfolios section in Kuwaiti Ministry of Trade and
Industry, said Wednesday that the three investment funds were
approved by the Central Bank of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
She said the ministry is about to issue necessary
recommendations for the marketing of these funds in Kuwait
according to laws and regulations.
</P>
<P>
The first fund called "the guaranteed return fund" with a
capital of 20 million dollars will be marketed by the
Bahrain-Kuwait Bank's Kuwait branch.
</P>
<P>
The second, "the international investor's first Kuwaiti
dinar fund", has a variable capital of a maximum of 150
million Kuwaiti dinars (around 495 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
The third, a general fund with a variable capital of a maximum
of 500 million dollars, will be marketed by the Kuwait and Middle
East Financial Investment Company, according to the chairwoman.
</P>
<P>
The funds will bring the total number of investment funds
marketed in Kuwait to 26, she said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
