<HEADLINE> Clinton Outlines New Plan for Teachers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 17 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
today proposed a new plan to coax teachers to the inner city and
rural communities with offers of scholarships for a three-year
commitment.
</P>
<P>
The president announced the initiative today in a speech before
the annual convention of the influential National Association for
the Advancement of Colored People (NAACP) at Pittsburgh,
Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said, "Far too many schools are not serving our
children well, and too many children from our inner cities and
poor rural areas are graduating without the skills they need."
</P>
<P>
Clinton promised to send legislation to Congress next month for
the scholarships, which will put special emphasis on recruiting
minorities.
</P>
<P>
He proposed a five-year program of 350 million U.S. dollars to
subsidize the tuition of 35,000 would-be teachers who agree to
work at least three years in urban and rural schools with high
concentrations of low-income families.
</P>
<P>
The plan is among a series of education initiatives outlined by
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
As a nation, Clinton told the NAACP, "we have not given much
thought not only to how we're going to heal our own wounds and our
old challenges, but how we're going to become one America in the
21st century. We need your help." 
</P>
