<HEADLINE> Southern African Airlines Adopt Code of Conduct </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 17 (Xinhua) -- More than 20 airlines of the
southern African countries have adopted a new code of conduct
aiming to provide for a degree of self-regulation, said an
official here today.
</P>
<P>
Airlines Association of Southern Africa Chief Executive John
Morrison said in a statement that the code of conduct would
assist various governments in its efforts to protect passengers
from financially unsound airlines and practices.
</P>
<P>
Among others, main aspects of the code include ensuring the
highest standard in dealing with the public, and assisting member
airlines in achieving adequate levels of profitability to satisfy
the association so that its members' operations are adequately
financed, said the statement.
</P>
<P>
The code would also promote safe, reliable, and secure air
services, and require the provision of high quality, value for
money, industry required products and services.
</P>
<P>
South African Airways, Air Namibia, Air Malawi, Air Mauritius,
Air Zimbabwe, Lesotho Airways, and Royal Swazi National Airways
are among those which signed the code of conduct. 
</P>
