<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Housing Starts in US Up 4.8 Percent in June </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 17 (Xinhua) -- Housing starts in the U.S. rose
by 4.8 percent in June and all regions except for the Northeast
posted gains, the U.S. Commerce Department reported today.
</P>
<P>
The department said that construction of new homes and
apartments totaled 1.45 million at a seasonally adjusted annual
rate, up from a revised 1.39 million in May.
</P>
<P>
It also said the U.S. housing starts declined by 6.6 percent in
May, even sharper than the 4.8 percent drop announced last month.
</P>
<P>
Single-family starts -- 80 percent of the total -- rose by 2.6
percent to a 1.11 million rate in June, the first increase in four
months.
</P>
<P>
Construction of apartments and condominiums -- often volatile
but not as sensitive to interest-rate changes -- shot up 12.9
percent to a 342,000 rate, nearly recouping a 13.4 percent loss a
month earlier.
</P>
<P>
Regionally, starts jumped by 11.2 percent in the South. They
were up by 1.1 percent in the West and 0.7 percent in the Midwest.
But the housing starts fell 6.6 percent in the Northeast.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, applications for building permits -- often a
barometer of future activity -- slipped 2.6 percent to a 1.40
million annual rate, the third straight decline.
</P>
<P>
Most analysts expected new construction in the U.S. to level
off this year after reaching an eight-year high of 1.48 million in
1996. For the year so far, starts totaled 3.2 percent less than
they did during the first six months of 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
