<HEADLINE> Freshman Lawmakers Introduce Campaign Finance Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 17 (Xinhua) -- A group of freshmen legislators
of the U.S. House of Representatives proposed today a campaign
finance bill that would ban unregulated "soft-money" donations.
</P>
<P>
The plan, endorsed by some 30 freshmen legislators, also would
require candidates for federal offices to provide more details
about their finances and more stringent disclosure for advocacy
groups advertising on TV and radio.
</P>
<P>
It would gradually increase, based on inflation, limits on
regulated campaign donations.
</P>
<P>
Representative Asa Hutchinson of Arkansas, leader of the
Republican contingent on the group, admitted they have received
little support from party leaders. Leadership opposition to a ban
on soft money -- the huge, largely unregulated donations to
political parties that are supposed to be used only for
party-building activities, was "a significant discouragement for
some of the freshmen," he said.
</P>
<P>
Hutchinson said there is "an intrigue with the status quo."
</P>
<P>
On the Democratic side, Representative Ellen Tauscher of
California said working on campaign finance provides "an
opportunity to be taken to the woodshed regularly."
</P>
<P>
Although dozens of campaign finance bills have been introduced
this year, there has been little legislative action on those
bills. 
</P>
</TEXT>
