<HEADLINE> US Government to Probe into UC Admissions Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 17 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. federal government has
opened probe into whether the school system's new race-blind
admissions policy discriminates against blacks and Hispanics in
three law schools of the University of California after their
sharp decline in minority enrollment this year.
</P>
<P>
In a letter sent to civil rights groups late last week, the
U.S. Education Department said it had "sufficient information" to
launch an investigation into admissions practices at UC's
Berkeley, Davis and Los Angeles law schools.
</P>
<P>
"We're looking at whether admissions policies discriminate,"
Education Department spokesman Rick Miller said.
</P>
<P>
The UC Berkeley announced that the number of black students
admitted to its Boalt Law School this year decreased by 81 percent
and the number of Hispanic students by 50 percent. None of the 14
black students accepted this year has chosen to attend.
</P>
<P>
The UC regents voted in 1995 to ban race, ethnicity and gender
in admissions. The policy first took effect with the graduate
school classes entering in the fall of 1997. It will apply to
undergraduates next year. 
</P>
