<HEADLINE> Action Plan for Tobacco Control in Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YAOUNDE, July 17 (Xinhua) -- An action plan for tobacco
control in Africa has been worked out at a just ended
International Workshop on Tobacco Control, local radio reported
today.
</P>
<P>
The action plan includes the adoption of comprehensive
policies including legislature by every African country to reduce
the social and economic use of tobacco for people's health.
</P>
<P>
It also calls for the provisional training for technical
assistance to increase awareness and capacity among government
ministers regarding the threat from tobacco use and from the
tobacco industry that targets African populations, especially
women and children.
</P>
<P>
According to the radio, the action plan will later be
presented for discussion and adoption by participants at the
"Africa Strategy Meeting" at the "World Conference on Smoking and
Health" billed for Beijing, China next month.
</P>
<P>
The International Workshop on Tobacco Control in Africa
started on July 13 and ended Wednesday. It was organized by the
Tobacco Control Commission of Africa.
</P>
<P>
For four days, experts drawn from nine African countries
focused their delebrations on methods of communication and
information, tobacco control and diseases prevention as priority
items on individual country's political agenda.
</P>
<P>
Africa is the only continent in the world that does not have
any tobacco control mission. It also does not have any regional
plan for action like the other continents. Therefore the action
plan drafted at this workshop has formulated practical, realistic
and attainable tobacco control objectives for Africa. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
