<HEADLINE> UNICEF Strives to Curb Child Malaria Deaths </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 17 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Children's Fund
(UNICEF) is to renew its efforts in reducing deaths from malaria
among children, especially in sub-Saharan Africa where 90 percent
of the deaths are recorded annually.
</P>
<P>
"Every year, malaria causes the death of one million children
under five in Africa alone, a toll that far exceeds the mortality
rate from AIDS," reported a UNICEF statement here today.
</P>
<P>
By the year 2000, it said, 20 percent of children under five
in areas prone to the disease will be sleeping under a bed net
dipped in environmental-friendly insecticides, while the rate
would increases to 50 percent by 2005.
</P>
<P>
The target is to have all children in endemic areas sleeping
under a bed net by the year 2010, the statement said, adding that
the lives of 500,000 children in Africa would be saved yearly in
the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
UNICEF promised to strengthen the capacity of African
institutes to provide expertise in malaria control on the
continent.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, control efforts are largely ignored by
industrialized countries which are less affected by the disease,
bringing about a shortage in funding for the disease, the
statement noted.
</P>
<P>
In 1993, according to UNICEF, funding for global malaria
research was only 84 million U.S. Dollars, compared to 2.3
billion Dollars on cancer research in the United States alone.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. agency said it would explore the use of vitamin A and
zinc as a way of reducing malaria morbidity, based on some
positive findings in recent research. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
