<HEADLINE> U.S. Senate Approves Increased Foreign Aid Budget </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 17 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Senate today approved
a foreign aid budget of 13.2 billion U.S. dollars for fiscal 1998,
one billion increase than the current fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
The Senate approved the budget, which starts Oct. 1, on a
strong bipartisan vote of 91-8. The increase comes after a 60
percent decline in foreign aid over the past ten years.
</P>
<P>
However, the funds still amounts to less than one percent of
the federal budget. It is 116 million U.S. dollars less than
President Bill Clinton requested.
</P>
<P>
The Senate also approved by a 95-4 vote a Republican-sponsored
amendment that cuts off aid to Russia if its proposed restrictions
on religious freedom became law and to Cambodia if it does not
freely and fairly elect its government.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Senate rejected a proposal by the Clinton
administration to end the annual certification process by which
countries are deemed to be fighting drugs and thus qualify for
U.S. aid.
</P>
<P>
According to the bill, Eastern Europe and the Baltic states
were given 485 million U.S. dollars and 800 million U.S. dollars
was set out for the states of the former Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
The bill also says that there will be no U.S. aid to the
Democratic Republic of the Congo until President Laurent Kabila
cooperates with international investigation of alleged mass
killings of Hutus. 
</P>
</TEXT>
