<HEADLINE> US Senate Approves Foreign Aid Increase </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 17 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Senate today
overwhelmingly approved a bill which would increase about one
billion dollars in foreign aid.
</P>
<P>
The bill, which was approved with a vote of 91 to 8, covers
economic and military assistance and export assistance for U.S.
goods and services totaling 13.2 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Although the Senate version of the bill is slightly below the
sum requested by the Clinton administration, it reverses a recent
trend in reducing foreign aid by adding 933 million dollars to
this year's funding level.
</P>
<P>
It provides the customary amounts of 3 billion dollars for
Israel, 2.1 billion for Egypt and 150 million for Jordan.
</P>
<P>
Although the foreign aid bill does not specify how much of the
800 million dollars provided for the former Soviet states would go
to Russia, the Clinton administration wants to give it 195 million
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Half of the 225 million available to the Ukraine will be
withheld pending administration certification of that nation's
efforts to end corruption.
</P>
<P>
A total of almost 1.8 billion dollars is provided for programs
to combat infectious diseases such as drug-resistant tuberculosis,
malaria, dengue fever and the ebola virus.
</P>
<P>
The House is expected to vote next week on its own measure,
which would allocate 12.3 billion dollars to foreign aid programs.
Differences between the two versions will have to be resolved in
conference before the joint bill is submitted to Clinton for his
signature. 
</P>
