<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AIDS Deaths Continue to Decline in US </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, July 17 (Xinhua) -- While AIDS deaths are on the
increase worldwide, AIDS deaths continue to decline in the Unites
States, and the trend is expected to go on, according to a latest
report of the New York Times.
</P>
<P>
The number of deaths dropped 19 percent, to 30,700 from 37,900,
in the first nine months of 1996, compared with the same period of
1995. Among women, the number of deaths dropped for the first
time.
</P>
<P>
"We have entered a new era in the H.I.V. epidemic, both in
terms of treatment and prevention," said Helene Gayle, who heads
the AIDS programs of the Centers for Disease Control and
Prevention, in Atlanta, a southern city of the United States.
</P>
<P>
The overall decline was attributed to greater access to medical
care and to development of newer drug therapies for both the AIDS
virus and infections that can occur as fatal complications of
AIDS.
</P>
<P>
But disproportionate rates of decline in AIDS deaths among men,
women and minority groups are worrisome to AIDS experts. Death of
women decreased by 7 percent, compared with the 22 percent decline
in deaths among men. While the number of deaths dropped 28 percent
for whites, the drop was 10 percent for blacks and 16 percent for
Hispanics.
</P>
<P>
The Centers for Disease Control estimates that there are from
600,000 to 900,000 infected people in the United States. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970718.0249 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Backs Expanding U.N. Security Council </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 17 (Xinhua) -- The United States today said
that it would support the permanent U.N. Security Council members
increased to ten, including three more seats for three developing
countries.
</P>
<P>
State Department spokesman Nicholas Burns told reporters that
the U.S. agrees that there ought to be "developing countries sit
on a permanent basis on the U.N. Security Council as permanent
members."
</P>
<P>
"We believe that the regions themselves -- the African
countries, the Latin American countries and the Asian countries --
ought to decide how these seats will be filled," he said.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. has long backed Germany and Japan as permanent members
of the UN Security Council, but has not indicated which developing
countries it favors.
</P>
<P>
Burns added that the U.S. has not taken a position on the veto
power for new permanent members including Germany and Japan.
</P>
<P>
But he stressed that the U.S. will "oppose any resolution which
infringes on prerogatives for current permanent members."
</P>
<P>
"We believe that this should be worked out and discussed,
specifically -- obviously, on the U.N. Security Council, " he
said, adding that the U.S. would favor the size of the Security
Council increased to 20 or 21 members.
</P>
<P>
"We believe that the regions themselves, the African countries,
the Latin countries and the Asian countries, ought to decide how
these seats will be filled," he said.
</P>
<P>
Burns said he expected the issue to be "very actively"
discussed throughout the next year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970718.0250 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canadian Bank Urges Ottawa to Lift Ban on Mergers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, July 17 (Xinhua) -- Canada's third largest bank, the
Bank of Montreal, has called for virtually all-out competition in
financial services, reports said today.
</P>
<P>
Under its proposals, Canada's domestic banks could merge,
foreign banks could buy into Canadian ones and the doors to
retailing insurance and asset leasing would be open wide.
</P>
<P>
"Canadian banks should not be prohibited from merging to meet
competition and therefore continue to provide their customers with
financial services at internationally competitive prices," said
Tim O'Neill, chief economist of the bank.
</P>
<P>
O'Neill made the remarks at a news conference where Bank of
Montreal unveiled its submission to a federal task force that is
examining the future of financial services in Canada.
</P>
<P>
The bank's proposals include asking that foreign banks be
allowed to increase their stakes in Canadian banks under certain
condition.
</P>
<P>
Currently, ownership in Canada's big banks by any single
interest is limited to 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, it proposed allowing mergers of Canadian
banks, to make them more competitive internationally and at home.
</P>
<P>
It also suggested opening up access to the Canadian payments
system to non-banks, insurers and retailers, for example, which
would then be able to issue checks and/or debit cards.
</P>
<P>
As well, it recommended loosening restrictions on selling
insurance and asset leasing.
</P>
<P>
As it now stands, Canadian banks are not allowed to sell
insurance in their branches and are confined to selling only
certain kinds of leases. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
