<HEADLINE> U.S. to Send Troops to Train Africans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 17 (Xinhua) -- Approximately 120 U.S. special
forces troops are preparing to go to Senegal and Uganda on July 21
to begin a U.S.-sponsored program of training African troops for
peacekeeping and humanitarian missions, the State Department said
on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"This initiative is compatible with the call at the Denver
summit for long term efforts to promote rapidly deployable African
peacekeeping capabilities," spokesman Nicholas Burns told
reporters.
</P>
<P>
At the Denver summit last month, several countries called for
long-range moves to develop such peacekeeping units so that the
United States and other non-African countries could minimize the
need to intervene in crises under the auspices of the United
Nations of the Organization of African Unity.
</P>
<P>
"We continue to work closely with France and the United
Kingdom, as well as many African countries to move towards the
establishment of an African peacekeeping support group," Burns
said. The U.S. special forces troops will train battalion-size
units in the two countries and Burns said training in other
nations will start shortly.
</P>
<P>
The other nations include Ethiopia, Mali, Malawi, Ghana and
Tunisia, according to reports. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
